# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: precision-agriculture
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] An **agricultural drone** is an unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV) used in agriculture operations, mostly in yield optimization by monitoring crop growth, aerial seeding and crop protection.
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] Agricultural drones provide information on crop growth stages, crop health, and soil variations.
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] Multispectral sensors are used on agricultural drones to image electromagnetic radiation beyond the visible spectrum, including near-infrared and short-wave infrared.
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] Agricultural UAVs are often fitted with spray equipment for pesticide application.
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] As drones entered use in agriculture, the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) encouraged farmers to use this new technology to monitor their fields.
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] However, with the unexpected boom of agricultural drones, the FAA quickly retracted such encouragement, pending new rules and regulations.
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] With incidents such as drones crashing into other agricultural aircraft, the FAA and the American Farm Bureau Federation (AFBF) began discussions to agree on regulations that would allow the beneficial use of such drones in a safe and efficient manner.
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] In 2016, the FAA published rules for commercial drone operations.
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] These rules require that commercial drone operators pass a knowledge exam, register their aircraft, and fly in accordance with published restrictions.
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] While satisfied overall with the rules, the American Farm Bureau Federation would like small adjustments to some of the restrictions that have been implemented.
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] Many countries, such as India, Malaysia, Singapore and Australia, have implemented laws regarding the use of drones.
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] Such laws are still nonexistent in many countries around the world, and 15 countries have outlawed all drone operations.
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] The EU plans to implement a common set of drone regulations for all of its members.
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] The use of agricultural drones has ethical and social implications.
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] One benefit is that they are able to monitor and control inputs as part of precision agriculture systems, that include minimizing the environmental impact of pesticides.
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] However, in the USA, drones do not require permission to fly over another person's property at altitudes of under 400 feet (120 m).
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] They may have microphones and cameras attached, and the resulting concern for potential privacy violation has caused some opposition towards drones..One other improvement with using drones is the precision that they operate with.
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] Other companies might start flying their drones in unregulated areas to survey their competition and the condition of their crops and agricultural yield.
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] There is a large capacity for growth in the area of agricultural drones.
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] With technology constantly improving, imaging of the crops will need to improve as well.
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] With the data that drones record from the crops the farmers are able to analyze their crops and make educated decisions on how to proceed given the accurate crop information.
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] Software programs for analyzing and correcting crop production have the potential to grow in this market.
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] Farmers will fly a drone over their crops, accurately identify an issue in a specific area, and take the necessary actions to correct the problem.
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] This gives the farmer time to focus on the overall task of production instead of spending time surveying their crops.
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] Additional uses include keeping track of livestock, surveying fences, and monitoring for plant pathogens.
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] Both the purchase and maintenance costs of modern drones make them too expensive for small farms in developing nations.
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] Pilot programs in Tanzania are focusing on minimizing those costs, producing agricultural drones simple and rugged enough to be repaired locally.
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] A research team from Washington State University has developed an automated drone system that deters pests like crows or European starlings from feeding on grapes and other crops.
[src:precision-agriculture/agricultural-drones] The birds could be scared off by the drone's noise, but researchers also could include distress calls and predatory bird noises.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] A **fertilizer** or **fertiliser** is any material of natural or synthetic origin that is applied to soil or to plant tissues to supply plant nutrients.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Fertilizers may be distinct from liming materials or other non-nutrient soil amendments.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Many sources of fertilizer exist, both natural and industrially produced.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] For most modern agricultural practices, fertilization focuses on three main macronutrients: nitrogen (N), phosphorus (P), and potassium (K) with occasional addition of supplements like rock flour for micronutrients.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Farmers apply these fertilizers in a variety of ways: through dry or pelletized or liquid application processes, using large agricultural equipment, or hand-tool methods.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Historically, fertilization came from natural or organic sources: compost, animal manure, human manure, harvested minerals, crop rotations, and byproducts of human-nature industries (e.g. fish processing waste, or bloodmeal from animal slaughter).
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] However, starting in the 19th century, after innovations in plant nutrition following Justus von Liebig's discoveries, an agricultural industry developed around synthetically created agrochemical fertilizers.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] This transition was important in transforming the global food system towards larger-scale industrial agriculture with large crop yields in monocultures.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The invention of Haber process for producing ammonia for nitrogen in the 20th century combined with amplified chemical production capacity created during World War II led to a boom in using nitrogen fertilizers.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] In the latter half of the 20th century, increased use of nitrogen fertilizers (800% increase between 1961 and 2019) has been a crucial component of the increased productivity of conventional food systems as part of the so-called "Green Revolution".
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Fertilizers, especially when applied excessively, can have environmental consequences such as water pollution and eutrophication due to nutrient runoff.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Additionally, the chemical process for creating the fertilizers results in byproducts, including carbon and other emissions.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] In some cases contamination and pollution of soil result by accumulation of heavy metals contained in some fertilizers collected through mining.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Sustainable agricultural practices, such as reduced tillage and planting buffer strips, can minimize these adverse environmental effects.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Management of soil fertility has preoccupied farmers since the beginning of agriculture.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Middle Eastern, Chinese, Mesoamerican, and cultures of the Central Andes were all early adopters of agriculture.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] This is thought to have led to their cultures growing faster in population which allowed an exportation of culture to neighboring hunter-gatherer groups.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Fertilizer use along with agriculture allowed some of these early societies a critical advantage over their neighbors, leading them to become dominant cultures in their respective regions.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Egyptians, Romans, Babylonians, and early Germans are all recorded as using minerals or manure to enhance the productivity of their farms.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The scientific research of plant nutrition started well before the work of German chemist Justus von Liebig although his name is most mentioned as the "father of the fertilizer industry".
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Nicolas Théodore de Saussure and scientific colleagues at the time were quick to disprove the simplifications of von Liebig.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Prominent scientists whom von Liebig drew were Carl Ludwig Sprenger and Hermann Hellriegel.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] In this field, a 'knowledge erosion' took place, partly driven by an intermingling of economics and research.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] John Bennet Lawes, an English entrepreneur, began experimenting on the effects of various manures on plants growing in pots in 1837, and a year or two later the experiments were extended to crops in the field.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] One immediate consequence was that in 1842 he patented a manure formed by treating phosphates with sulfuric acid, and thus was the first to create the artificial manure industry.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] In the succeeding year, he enlisted the services of Joseph Henry Gilbert; together they performed crop experiments at the Institute of Arable Crops Research.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The Birkeland–Eyde process was one of the competing industrial processes at the beginning of nitrogen-based fertilizer production.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] This process was used to fix atmospheric nitrogen (N2) into nitric acid (HNO3), one of several chemical processes called nitrogen fixation.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The resultant nitric acid was then used as a source of nitrate (NO3−).
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] A factory based on the process was built in Rjukan and Notodden in Norway and large hydroelectric power facilities were built.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The 1910s and 1920s witnessed the rise of the Haber process and the Ostwald process.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The Haber process produces ammonia (NH3) from methane (CH4) (natural gas) and molecular nitrogen (N2) from the air.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The ammonia from the Haber process is then partially converted into nitric acid (HNO3) in the Ostwald process.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] It is estimated that a third of annual global food production uses ammonia from the Haber–Bosch process and that this supports nearly half the world's population.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] After World War II, nitrogen production plants that had ramped up for wartime bomb manufacturing were pivoted towards agricultural uses.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The use of synthetic nitrogen fertilizers has increased steadily over the last 50 years of the 20th century, rising almost 20-fold to a rate of 100 million tonnes of nitrogen per year in 2003.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The development of synthetic nitrogen fertilizers has significantly supported global population growth.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] It has been estimated that almost half the people on the Earth are currently fed due to synthetic nitrogen fertilizer use.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The use of phosphate fertilizers has also increased from 9 million tonnes per year in 1960 to 40 million tonnes per year in 2000, but future phosphorus fertilizer availability is now a critical issue.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Agricultural use of inorganic fertilizers in 2021 was 195 million tonnes of nutrients, of which 56% was nitrogen.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Asia represented 53% of the world's total agricultural use of inorganic fertilizers in 2021, followed by the Americas (29%), Europe (12%), Africa (4%) and Oceania (2%).
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] This ranking of the regions is the same for all nutrients.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The main users of inorganic fertilizers are, in descending order, China, India, Brazil, and the United States of America (see Table 15), with China the largest user of each nutrient.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Agricultural use of inorganic fertilizers in 2023 was 190 million tonnes of nutrients, of which 112 million tonnes (58%) was nitrogen.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] A maize crop yielding 6–9 tonnes of grain per hectare (2.5 acres) requires 31–50 kilograms (68–110 lb) of phosphate fertilizer to be applied; soybean crops require about half, 20–25 kg per hectare.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Yara International is the world's largest producer of nitrogen-based fertilizers.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Fertilizers enhance the growth of plants.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] This goal is met in two ways, the traditional one being additives that provide nutrients.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The second mode by which some fertilizers act is to enhance the effectiveness of the soil by modifying its water-holding capacity and aeration.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] This article, like many on fertilizers, emphasizes the nutritional aspect.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Although calcium uptake by plant roots has long-time been considered as luxury consumption, it is now considered as an essential element for its various roles in the maintenance of the integrity of plant cell walls and cell membranes.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The nutrients required for healthy plant life are classified according to the elements, but the elements are not used as fertilizers.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Instead, compounds containing these elements are the basis of fertilizers.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Macro-nutrients are present in plant tissue in quantities from 0.15% to 6.0% on a dry matter (DM) (0% moisture) basis but they are sometimes consumed in larger quantities than required (luxury consumption), in particular when fertilizers are used in excess of plant requirements (overfertilization).
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Plants are made up of four main elements: hydrogen, oxygen, carbon, and nitrogen.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Carbon, hydrogen, and oxygen are widely available respectively in carbon dioxide and in water.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Although nitrogen makes up most of the atmosphere, it is in a form that is unavailable to plants.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Nitrogen is the most important fertilizer since nitrogen is present in proteins (amide bonds between amino acids), DNA (puric and pyrimidic bases), and other components (e.g., tetrapyrrolic heme in chlorophyll).
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] It is common tenet that nitrogen is absent from the parent rock and thus cannot be obtained from mineral weathering, although recent studies point to the equal importance of the atmosphere and bedrock as nitrogen sources.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Nitrogen is made available to plants through weathering of nitrogen-containing parent rocks and nitrogen fixation.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] *Clostridium*) and symbiotic bacteria living in root systems of host plants (notably legumes) can fix atmospheric nitrogen (N2) by converting it to ammonia (NH3) and amino acids which are available to plants.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Phosphate (PO3−4) is required for the production of DNA (genetic code) and ATP, the main energy carrier in cells, as well as certain lipids (phospholipids, the main components of the lipidic double layer of the cell membranes).
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Two sets of enzymatic reactions are highly relevant to the efficiency of nitrogen-based fertilizers.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The first is the hydrolysis (reaction with water) of urea (CO(NH2)2).
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Many soil bacteria possess the enzyme urease, which catalyzes the conversion of urea to ammonium ion (NH+4) and bicarbonate ion (HCO−3).
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Ammonia-oxidizing bacteria (AOB), such as species of *Nitrosomonas*, oxidize ammonia (NH3) to nitrite (NO−2), a process termed nitrification.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Nitrite-oxidizing bacteria, especially *Nitrobacter*, oxidize nitrite (NO−2) to nitrate (NO−3), which is extremely soluble and mobile, being leached easily to groundwater then to rivers then to the sea, and is a major cause of eutrophication and algal blooms in rivers, lakes and sea shores.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Fertilizers are classified in several ways.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] They are classified according to whether they provide a single nutrient (e.g., K, P, or N), in which case they are classified as *straight fertilizers*.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] *Multinutrient fertilizers* (or *complex fertilizers*) provide two or more nutrients, for example, N and P combined.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Fertilizers are also sometimes classified as inorganic (the topic of most of this article) versus organic.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Inorganic fertilizers exclude carbon-containing materials except urea.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Organic fertilizers are usually (recycled) plant- or animal-derived matter (e.g. compost, manure, respectively).
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Inorganic are sometimes called synthetic fertilizers since various chemical treatments are required for their manufacture.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] A mixture of single superphosphate and triple superphosphate is called double superphosphate.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] More than 90% of a typical superphosphate fertilizer is water-soluble.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The main potassium-based straight fertilizer is muriate of potash (MOP, 95–99% KCl).
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] It is typically available as 0-0-60 or 0-0-62 fertilizer.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] They consist of two or more nutrient components.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Major two-component fertilizers provide both nitrogen and phosphorus to the plants.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] About 85% of MAP and DAP fertilizers are soluble in water.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] NPK fertilizers are three-component fertilizers providing nitrogen, phosphorus, and potassium.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] There exist two types of NPK fertilizers: compound and blends.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Compound NPK fertilizers contain chemically bound ingredients, while blended NPK fertilizers are physical mixtures of single nutrient components.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] NPK rating is a rating system describing the amount of nitrogen, phosphorus, and potassium in a fertilizer.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] NPK ratings consist of three numbers separated by dashes (e.g., 10-10-10 or 16–4–8) describing the chemical content of fertilizers.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The first number represents the percentage of nitrogen in the product; the second number, P2O5; the third, K2O.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Fertilizers do not actually contain P2O5 or K2O, but the system is a conventional shorthand for the amount of phosphorus (P) or potassium (K) in a fertilizer.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] A 50-pound (23 kg) bag of fertilizer labeled 16-4-8 contains 8 lb (3.6 kg) of nitrogen (16% of the 50 pounds), an amount of phosphorus equivalent to that in 2 pounds of P2O5 (4% of 50 pounds), and 4 pounds of K2O (8% of 50 pounds).
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Most fertilizers are labeled according to this N-P-K convention, although Australian convention, following an N-P-K-S system, adds a fourth number for sulfur, and uses elemental values for all values including P and K.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Micronutrients are consumed in smaller quantities and are present in plant tissue on the order of parts-per-million (ppm), ranging from 0.15 to 400 ppm or less than 0.04% dry matter.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] These elements are often required as co-enzymes for enzymes essential to the plant's metabolism.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Because these elements enable catalysts (enzymes), their impact far exceeds their concentration.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Typical micronutrients are boron, zinc, molybdenum, iron, and manganese.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] These elements are provided as water-soluble salts.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Iron presents special problems because it converts from soluble (ferrous) to insoluble bio-unavailable (ferric) compounds at moderate soil pH and phosphate concentrations.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] For this reason, iron is often administered as a chelate complex, e.g., the EDTA or EDDHA derivatives.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The micronutrient needs depend on the plant and the environment.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] For example, sugar beets appear to require boron, and legumes require cobalt, while environmental conditions such as heat or drought make boron less available for plants, causing boron deficiency.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The production of synthetic, or inorganic, fertilizers require prepared chemicals, whereas organic fertilizers are derived from the biological processing of plant and animal remains or excreta (e.g. urine, feces).
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Nitrogen fertilizers are made from ammonia (NH3) produced by the Haber–Bosch process.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] In this energy-intensive process, natural gas (CH4) usually supplies the hydrogen, and the nitrogen (N2) is derived from the air.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] This ammonia is used as a feedstock for all other nitrogen fertilizers, such as anhydrous ammonium nitrate (NH4NO3) and urea (CO(NH2)2).
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Deposits of sodium nitrate (NaNO3) (Chilean saltpeter) are also found in the Atacama Desert in Chile and were one of the original (1830) nitrogen-rich fertilizers used.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Nitrates are also produced from ammonia by the Ostwald process.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Phosphate fertilizers are obtained by extraction from phosphate rock, which contains two principal phosphorus-containing minerals, fluorapatite Ca5(PO4)3F (CFA) and hydroxyapatite Ca5(PO4)3OH.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Billions of kg of phosphate rock are mined annually, but the size and quality of the remaining ore is decreasing.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] These minerals are converted into water-soluble phosphate salts by treatment with acids.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The large production of sulfuric acid is primarily motivated by this application.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] In the nitrophosphate process or Odda process (invented in 1927), phosphate rock with up to a 20% phosphorus (P) content is dissolved with nitric acid (HNO3) to produce a mixture of phosphoric acid (H3PO4) and calcium nitrate (Ca(NO3)2).
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] This mixture can be combined with a potassium fertilizer to produce a *compound fertilizer* with the three macronutrients N, P and K in easily dissolved form.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Potash is a mixture of potassium minerals used to make potassium (chemical symbol: K) fertilizers.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Potash is soluble in water, so the main effort in producing this nutrient from the ore involves some purification steps, e.g., to remove sodium chloride (NaCl) (common salt).
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Sometimes potash is referred to as K2O, as a matter of convenience to those describing the potassium content.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] In fact, potash fertilizers are usually potassium chloride, potassium sulfate, potassium carbonate, or potassium nitrate.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Nitrophosphates are made by acidiculating phosphate rock with nitric acid.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] It is important to remove the calcium nitrate because calcium nitrate is extremely hygroscopic.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Fertilizers of an organic origin (the first definition) include animal wastes, plant wastes from agriculture, seaweed, compost, and treated sewage sludge (biosolids).
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Beyond manures, animal sources can include products from animal slaughters: bloodmeal, bone meal, feather meal, hides, hoofs, and horns all are typical components.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Organically derived materials available to industry such as sewage sludge may not be acceptable components of organic farming and gardening, because of factors ranging from residual contaminants to public perception.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] No matter the definition nor composition, most of these products contain less-concentrated nutrients, and the nutrients are not as easily quantified.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] They can offer soil-building advantages as well as be appealing to those who are trying to farm or garden more naturally.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] In terms of volume, peat is the most widely used packaged organic soil amendment.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] It is an immature form of coal which improves soil aeration and moisture and thus soil biological activity but confers no direct nutritional value to the plants.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] It is therefore not a fertilizer as defined in the beginning of the article, but rather an amendment.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Coir (derived from coconut husks), bark, and sawdust are mainly applied as mulch and protects the soil from desiccation while preventing the development of weeds and improving soil structure, but do not confer any nutritional value to the soil.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Some organic additives can even have a reverse effect on nutrients.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Fresh sawdust can consume soil nutrients as it breaks down and is colonized by wood-decay fungi, causing nitrogen deficiency (nitrogen drawdown) in the absence of nutrient addition.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] However, this property can be used to capture excess mineral nitrogen.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] These same organic soil texturizers (as well as compost, etc.) may increase the availability of nutrients through improved cation-exchange capacity, or through increased growth of microorganisms that in turn increase availability of certain plant nutrients.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] True organic fertilizers such as composts and manures may be distributed locally without going into industry production, making actual consumption more difficult to quantify.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] China has become the largest producer and consumer of nitrogen fertilizers while Africa has little reliance on nitrogen fertilizers.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Agricultural and chemical minerals are very important in industrial use of fertilizers, which is valued at approximately $200 billion.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Nitrogen has a significant impact in the global mineral use, followed by potash and phosphate.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The production of nitrogen has drastically increased since the 1960s.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Phosphate and potash have increased in price since the 1960s, which is larger than the consumer price index.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Potash is produced in Canada, Russia and Belarus, together making up over half of the world production.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Potash production in Canada rose in 2017 and 2018 by 18.6%.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Conservative estimates report 30 to 50% of crop yields are attributed to natural or synthetic commercial fertilizers.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Fertilizer consumption has surpassed the amount of farmland in the United States.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Data on the fertilizer consumption per hectare arable land in 2012 are published by The World Bank.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The diagram below shows fertilizer consumption by the European Union (EU) countries as kilograms per hectare (pounds per acre).
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The total consumption of fertilizer in the EU reached a peak of 11.6 million tons in 2017 but decreased steadily since that time, down to 9.3 million tons in 2023 for 157 million hectares arable land area in 2020, 1.5 million hectares less than in 2010.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] This figure equates to 70 kg of fertilizers consumed per ha arable land on average by the EU countries in 2020.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Total agricultural use of inorganic fertilizers, expressed as the sum of the three nutrients nitrogen (N), phosphorus (expressed as P2 O5 ) and potassium (expressed as K2 O), was 190 million tonnes in 2023, up 1% compared with 2022.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] 112 million tonnes of nitrogen (58% of the total), 41 million tonnes of phosphorus (21% ) and 38 million tonnes of potassium (20% ).
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Overall fertilizer use in 2023 was 55 million tonnes (41%) higher than in 2000 (38% higher for nitrogen, 26% higher for phosphorus and 73% higher for potassium).
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Asia represented 56% of world total agricultural use of inorganic fertilizers in 2023, followed by the Americas (27% ), Europe (11%), Africa (4%) and Oceania (2%).
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Fertilizers are commonly used for growing all crops, with application rates depending on soil fertility, usually as measured by a soil test and according to the particular crop.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Legumes, for example, fix nitrogen from the atmosphere and generally do not require nitrogen fertilizer, hence their promising use for ensuring agriculture sustainability.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The timing of application of fertilizers (here only mineral fertilizers will be considered) is a function of crop requirements, weather condition and market opportunities.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] It varies in nature and amount according to the type of agriculture (e.g. intensive farming versus conservation agriculture, grassland versus arable land), and the presence or absence of signs of nutrient deficiencies.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Timing fertilization with peak nutrient uptake demand is essential for optimizing both yield and quality.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] In general, nutrient uptake rates are highest from early to midgrowing season, which is why fertilization near the time of seeding is generally very effective.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] With fall-planted grains (e.g. winter wheat), fall N fertilization followed by spring topdressing is likely the best combination of fertilization practices to optimize yield.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The application of a soluble mineral fertilizer (e.g. ammonium nitrate) is avoided during heavy rainfall because most of it would be lost for the crop and would rapidly pollute the aquifer.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] After harvest of a main crop (e.g. wheat, maize, potatoes) a catch crop can be sown, using plant species with a rapid growth rate and high demand of nitrogen (e.g. white mustard).
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] This allows excess nitrogen, in particular the very mobile nitrate anion, to be taken up and transformed in plant proteins before contaminating the groundwater, and the associated geochemical processes, which would rapidly occur in the absence of plant cover.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The catch crop is further buried, allowing its transformation in humus in which nitrogen is fixed according to various stable chemical bonds.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Fertilizers are applied to crops both as solids and as liquid.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] About 90% of fertilizers are applied as solids.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The most widely used solid inorganic fertilizers are urea, diammonium phosphate and potassium chloride.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Solid fertilizer is typically granulated or powdered.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Often solids are available as prills, a solid globule.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Liquid fertilizers comprise aqueous solutions of ammonia, aqueous solutions of ammonium nitrate or urea.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] These concentrated products may be diluted with water to form a concentrated liquid fertilizer (e.g., UAN).
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Advantages of liquid fertilizer are its more rapid effect and easier coverage.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The addition of fertilizer to irrigation water is called *fertigation*.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Granulated fertilizers are more economical to ship and store, not to mention easier to apply.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] A **controlled-release fertiliser** (**CRF**) is a granulated fertiliser that releases nutrients gradually into the soil (i.e., with a controlled release period).
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Controlled-release fertilizer is also known as *controlled-availability fertilizer*, *delayed-release fertilizer*, *metered-release fertilizer*, or *slow-acting fertilizer*.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Usually slow- and controlled-release fertilizers refer to nitrogen-based fertilizers, e.g. ureaform, needing degradation by a wide spectrum of soil organisms before nitrogen could be liberated as nitrate.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Slow-release fertilizers (SRF) and controlled-release fertilizers (CRF) offer various benefits over conventional ones, ensuring sustainability in fertilizing practice.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Foliar fertilizers are applied directly to leaves.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] They can reduce the total amounts of fertilizer applied and achieve high fertilizer efficiency.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] This method is almost invariably used to apply water-soluble straight nitrogen fertilizers and used especially for high-value crops such as fruits.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Urea is the most common foliar fertilizer.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] However, chelation of the foliar-applied nutrient is recommended for improving absorption and migration of the targeted nutrient and thereby avoiding loss to the soil and the groundwater.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Various chemicals are used to enhance the efficiency of nitrogen-based fertilizers.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] In this way farmers can limit the polluting effects of nitrogen run-off.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Nitrification inhibitors (also known as nitrogen stabilizers) suppress the conversion of ammonia into nitrate, an anion that is more prone to leaching.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] 1-Carbamoyl-3-methylpyrazole (CMP), dicyandiamide, nitrapyrin (2-chloro-6-trichloromethylpyridine) and 3,4-dimethylpyrazole phosphate (DMPP) are popular.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Urease inhibitors are used to slow the hydrolytic conversion of urea into ammonia catalyzed by ureases, ammonia being prone to evaporation as well as nitrification.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] A popular inhibitor of ureases is *N*-(*n*-butyl)thiophosphoric triamide (NBPT).
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Careful use of fertilization technologies is important because excess nutrients can be detrimental to the cultivated plant.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Fertilizer burn can occur when too much fertilizer is applied, resulting in damage or even death of the plant.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Fertilizers vary in their tendency to burn roughly in accordance with their salt index.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Synthetic fertilizers used in agriculture have wide-reaching environmental consequences.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] According to the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) Special Report on Climate Change and Land, production of these fertilizers and associated land use practices are drivers of global warming.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The use of fertilizer has also led to a number of direct environmental consequences: agricultural runoff which leads to downstream effects like ocean dead zones and waterway contamination, soil microbiome degradation, and accumulation of toxic compounds in ecosystems.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] In order to mitigate environmental and food security concerns, the international community has included food systems in Sustainable Development Goal 2 which focuses on creating a climate-friendly and sustainable food production system.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] For each ton of phosphoric acid produced by the processing of phosphate rock, five tons of waste are generated.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] This waste takes the form of impure, useless, radioactive solid called phosphogypsum.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Estimates range from 100,000,000 and 280,000,000 tons of phosphogypsum waste produced annually worldwide.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Phosphorus and nitrogen fertilizers can affect soil, surface water, and groundwater due to the dispersion of minerals into waterways under high rainfall, snowmelt and can leach into groundwater over time.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Agricultural run-off is a major contributor to the eutrophication of freshwater bodies.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] For example, in the US, about half of all the lakes surveyed by the United States Environmental Protection Agency (US EPA) were eutrophic in 2007 with a further alarming increase to 80 per cent in 2012.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The main contributor to eutrophication is phosphate, which is normally a limiting nutrient, besides nitrogen; high P concentrations promote the growth of cyanobacteria and algae, the demise of which consumes oxygen.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Cyanobacteria blooms ('algal blooms') can also produce harmful toxins that can accumulate in the food chain, and can be harmful to humans.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Fertilizer run-off can be reduced by using weather-optimized fertilization strategies.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The nitrogen-rich compounds found in fertilizer runoff are the primary cause of serious oxygen depletion in many parts of oceans, especially in coastal zones, lakes and rivers.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The resulting lack of dissolved oxygen greatly reduces the ability of these areas to sustain oceanic fauna.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The number of oceanic dead zones near inhabited coastlines is increasing.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] As of 2006, the application of nitrogen fertilizer is being increasingly controlled in northwestern Europe and the United States.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] In cases where eutrophication can be reversed, it may nevertheless take decades and need significant soil management before the accumulated nitrates in groundwater can be broken down by natural denitrification.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Only a fraction of the nitrogen-based fertilizers is converted to plant matter.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The remainder accumulates in the soil or is lost as run-off.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] High application rates of nitrogen-containing fertilizers combined with the high water solubility of nitrate leads to increased runoff into surface water as well as leaching into groundwater, thereby causing groundwater pollution.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The excessive use of nitrogen-containing fertilizers (be they synthetic or natural) is particularly damaging, as much of the nitrogen that is not taken up by plants is transformed into nitrate which is easily leached.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Nitrate levels above 10 mg/L (10 ppm) in groundwater can cause 'blue baby syndrome' (acquired methemoglobinemia).
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The nutrients, especially nitrates, in fertilizers can cause problems for natural habitats and for human health if they are washed off into watercourses or leached through the soil into groundwater.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Run-off can lead to fertilizing algal blooms that use up all the oxygen and leave huge "dead zones" behind where other fish and aquatic life can not live.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Soil acidification refers to the process by which the pH level of soil becomes more acidic over time.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Soil pH is a measure of the soil's acidity or alkalinity and is determined on a scale from 0 to 14, with 7 being neutral.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] A pH value below 7 indicates acidic soil, while a pH value above 7 indicates alkaline or basic soil.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Soil acidification is a significant concern in agriculture and horticulture, leading to cation leaching, unstable soil aggregate structure, metal toxicity, decreased nutrient availability, and thus affecting soil biological properties and plant performances.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Nitrogen-containing fertilizers release ammonium or nitrate ions, which can acidify the soil as they undergo biochemical reactions.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] When nitrogen-containing fertilizers, whether mineral or organic, are added to the soil, they increase the concentration of hydrogen ions (H+) in the soil solution, which lowers the pH of the soil.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] This may lead to decrease in nutrient availability which may be offset by liming.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Soil acidification occurs also through acid rain, a man-induced concern despite severe measures to suppress or mitigate industrial gas emissions since the 1970s.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Among reported causes of acid rain, nitrogen fertilizers (whether mineral or organic), and the subsequent emissions of nitrous and nitric oxides are prominent in regions of intensive agriculture.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The mechanisms are complex, involving ammonia volatilization from manure (whether stored or spread) or urea and direct redeposition followed by nitrification in the soil or previous oxidation to nitrogen oxides in the atmosphere before redeposition as nitric acid.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The concentration of cadmium in phosphorus-containing fertilizers varies considerably and can be problematic.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] For example, mono-ammonium phosphate fertilizer may have a cadmium content of as low as 0.14 mg/kg or as high as 50.9 mg/kg.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The phosphate rock used in their manufacture can contain as much as 188 mg/kg cadmium Examples are deposits on Nauru and the Christmas Islands.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Continuous use of high-cadmium fertilizer can contaminate soils and plants.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Limits to the cadmium content of phosphate fertilizers have been considered by the European Commission.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Producers of phosphorus-containing fertilizers now select phosphate rock based on the cadmium content.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Phosphate rocks contain high levels of fluoride in the form of fluorapatite.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Consequently, the widespread use of phosphate fertilizers has increased soil fluoride concentrations.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] It has been found that food contamination from fertilizer is of little concern as plants accumulate little fluoride from the soil; of greater concern is the possibility of fluoride toxicity to livestock that ingest contaminated soil.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Also of possible concern are the effects of fluoride on soil microorganisms.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The radioactive content of the fertilizers varies considerably and depends both on their concentrations in the parent mineral and on the fertilizer production process.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Uranium-238 concentrations can range from 7 to 100 pCi/g (picocuries per gram) in phosphate rock and from 1 to 67 pCi/g in phosphate fertilizers.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Where high annual rates of phosphorus fertilizer are used, this can result in uranium-238 concentrations in soils and drainage waters that are several times greater than are normally present.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] However, the impact of these increases on the risk to human health from radionuclidic contamination of foods is very small (less than 0.05 mSv/y).
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Steel industry wastes such as steel slag are often recycled as a soil amendment or for the production of fertilizers due to their high Ca and Mg content and various trace elements necessary for plant growth.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] However, they can also include toxic metals.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Among them are arsenic, cadmium, chromium, and nickel, while steel slag amendment rather contribute to immobilize lead in the soil and thus to decrease its toxicity to the cultivated plant.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The most common toxic elements in this type of fertilizer are mercury, lead, and arsenic.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Given the high cost of removing potentially harmful properties from steel slags, a better solution is to immobilize them.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The incorporation of biochar to steel slag make even the mixture a good amendement for the (passivation) of heavy metals in agricultural soil.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Highly pure fertilizers are widely available and perhaps best known as the highly water-soluble fertilizers containing blue dyes used around households, such as Miracle-Gro.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] These highly water-soluble fertilizers are used in the plant nursery business and are available in larger packages at significantly less cost than retail quantities.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Some inexpensive retail granular garden fertilizers are made with high purity ingredients.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Attention has been addressed to the decreasing concentrations of micronutrients such as iron, zinc, copper and magnesium in many foods over the last 50–60 years.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Intensive farming practices, including the use of synthetic fertilizers, are frequently suggested as reasons for these declines and organic farming is often suggested as a solution.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] It is, therefore, unlikely that organic farming or reduced use of fertilizers (e.g. conservation agriculture) will solve the problem; foods with high nutrient density are posited to be achieved using older, lower-yielding varieties or the development of new high-yield, nutrient-dense varieties.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Fertilizers are, in fact, more likely to solve trace mineral deficiency problems than cause them: in Western Australia deficiencies of zinc, copper, manganese, iron and molybdenum were identified as limiting the growth of broad-acre crops and pastures in the 1940s and 1950s.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Soils in Western Australia are very old, highly weathered and deficient in many of the major nutrients and trace elements.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Since this time these trace elements are routinely added to fertilizers used in agriculture in this state.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Many other soils around the world are deficient in zinc, leading to deficiency in both plants and humans, and zinc fertilizers are widely used to solve this problem.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] High levels of fertilizer may cause the breakdown of the symbiotic relationships between plant roots and mycorrhizal fungi, in particular when in excess of plant requirements.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] It is still debated whether and how fertilizers affect soil animals.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Both organic and organic–mineral fertilizers increase the abundance of soil fauna whereas mineral fertilizers had no such effect, with idiosyncratic responses of soil animal groups masking overall effects.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Chemical fertilizers stimulates the growth of microbial populations but did not change their richness and diversity, while decreases in enzymatic activity have been registered.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The combination of soil acidification and high nitrogen content was probably unknown to most soil organisms before the advent of industrial agriculture.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] More generally, soils are either acidic and nutrient-poor, or neutral to basic and nutrient-rich (nitrogen included), in relation to the pH-dependent capacity of clay minerals to hold nutrients.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] This unexpected combination of excess nutrient availability and acid stress causes a depletion in the sustainability of animal and microbial communities by weakening the linkages between aboveground and belowground components of agroecosystems.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Other ecosystems are also affected by nitrogen-enriched acid rains originationg from intensive agricultural practices.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Sphagnum bogs are now shifting from carbon sinks (thanks to the accumulation of recalcitrant sphagnum litter and anoxic conditions) to carbon sources under the influence of nitrogen deposition and subsequent stimulation of decomposer activity.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Other nutrient-poor ecosystems are also strongly affected, such as heathlands, with a surprising combination of higher soil organic matter accumulation and higher soil enzyme activity.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Two types of agricultural management practices include organic farming and conventional agriculture.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The former encourages soil fertility using local resources to maximize efficiency.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Organic agriculture avoids synthetic agrochemicals.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Conventional agriculture uses all the components that organic agriculture does not use.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The excess use of organic amendments (e.g. pig slurry) may have detrimental effects on water quality through contamination of the aquifer and subsequent eutrophication of the water bodies it feds.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] This is a societal concern in areas where pig farming conflicts with environmental protection.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Most synthetic fertilizer is fed from fossil fuel, using fossil energy and methane for producing hydrogen used in the synthesis of ammonia by the Haber process, as well as various chemical reactions used in the synthesis of most fertilizers (e.g. urea, ammonium nitrate, superphosphate).
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Some alternatives have been proposed for the production of hydrogen, such as solar energy, waste treatment, or electrolysis.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The amount of greenhouse gases carbon dioxide, methane and nitrous oxide produced during the manufacture and use of nitrogen fertilizer is estimated as around 5% of anthropogenic greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] One third is produced during the production and two thirds during the use of fertilizers.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Nitrate is converted by soil bacteria to nitrous oxide, a greenhouse gas.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Nitrous oxide emissions by humans, most of which are from fertilizer, between 2007 and 2016 were estimated at 700 million tons of CO2 equivalent.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Nitrogen fertilizer was used at a rate of about 110 million tons (of N) per year in 2012.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Nitrous oxide (N2O) is the third most important greenhouse gas after carbon dioxide and methane.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] It has 296 times greater greenhouse effect per ton than carbon dioxide.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] The 2025 emissions contributed the equivalent of 700 megatons of CO2 to the atmosphere.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] It also contributes to stratospheric ozone depletion.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Altering processes and procedures could reduce these emissions.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] Methane emissions from crop fields (notably rice paddy fields) are increased by the application of ammonium-based fertilizers.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p01] These emissions contribute to global climate change as methane is a potent greenhouse gas.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p02] In Europe, problems with high nitrate concentrations in runoff are being addressed by the European Union's Nitrates Directive.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p02] Within Britain, farmers are encouraged to manage their land more sustainably in 'catchment-sensitive farming'.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p02] In the US, high concentrations of nitrate and phosphorus in runoff and drainage water are classified as nonpoint source pollutants due to their diffuse origin; this pollution is regulated at the state level.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p02] Oregon and Washington, both in the United States, have fertilizer registration programs with on-line databases listing chemical analyses of fertilizers.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p02] Carbon emission trading and eco-tariffs affect the production and price of fertilizer.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p02] In China, regulations have been implemented to control the use of N fertilizers in farming.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p02] In 2008, Chinese governments began to partially withdraw fertilizer subsidies, including subsidies to fertilizer transportation and to electricity and natural gas use in the industry.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p02] In consequence, the price of fertilizer has gone up and large-scale farms have begun to use less fertilizer.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p02] If large-scale farms keep reducing their use of fertilizer subsidies, they have no choice but to optimize the fertilizer they have which would therefore gain an increase in both grain yield and profit.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p02] In March 2022, the United States Department of Agriculture announced a new $250M grant to promote American fertilizer production.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p02] Part of the Commodity Credit Corporation, the grant program will support fertilizer production that is independent of dominant fertilizer suppliers, made in America, and utilizing innovative production techniques to jumpstart future competition.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p02] In the European Union The Russo-Ukrainian war and the subsequent strong increase in energy and mineral fertiliser prices highlighted the need for greater autonomy and efficiency in the production and use of fertilisers.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p02] The amended Temporary Crisis and Transition Framework for State Aid enabled EU countries to provide specific support to farmers and fertiliser producers.
[src:precision-agriculture/fertilizer-p02] Funds generated by measures such as the cap on the market revenues of certain electricity generators and the solidarity contribution can also be used, subject to the applicable conditions, for purposes of national support schemes.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] A **geographic information system** (**GIS**) consists of integrated computer hardware and software that store, manage, analyze, edit, output, and visualize geographic data.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Much of this often happens within a spatial database; however, this is not essential to meet the definition of a GIS.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] In a broader sense, one may consider such a system also to include human users and support staff, procedures and workflows, the body of knowledge of relevant concepts and methods, and institutional organizations.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The uncounted plural, *geographic information systems*, also abbreviated GIS, is the most common term for the industry and profession concerned with these systems.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The academic discipline that studies these systems and their underlying geographic principles, may also be abbreviated as GIS, but the unambiguous GIScience is more common.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] GIScience is often considered a subdiscipline of geography within the branch of technical geography.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Geographic information systems are used in multiple technologies, processes, techniques and methods.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] They are attached to various operations and numerous applications, that relate to: engineering, planning, management, transport/logistics, insurance, telecommunications, and business, as well as the natural sciences such as forestry, ecology, and Earth science.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] For this reason, GIS and location intelligence applications are at the foundation of location-enabled services, which rely on geographic analysis and visualization.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] GIS provides the ability to relate previously unrelated information, through the use of location as the "key index variable".
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Locations and extents that are found in the Earth's spacetime are able to be recorded through the date and time of occurrence, along with x, y, and z coordinates; representing, longitude (*x*), latitude (*y*), and elevation (*z*).
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] All Earth-based, spatial–temporal, location and extent references should be relatable to one another, and ultimately, to a "real" physical location or extent.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] This key characteristic of GIS has begun to open new avenues of scientific inquiry and studies.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] While digital GIS dates to the mid-1960s, when Roger Tomlinson first coined the phrase "geographic information system", many of the geographic concepts and methods that GIS automates date back decades earlier.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] One of the first known instances in which spatial analysis was used came from the field of epidemiology in the *Rapport sur la marche et les effets du choléra dans Paris et le département de la Seine* (1832).
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] French cartographer and geographer Charles Picquet created a map outlining the forty-eight districts in Paris, using halftone color gradients, to provide a visual representation for the number of reported deaths due to cholera per every 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] In 1854, John Snow, an epidemiologist and physician, was able to determine the source of a cholera outbreak in London through the use of spatial analysis.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Snow achieved this through plotting the residence of each casualty on a map of the area, as well as the nearby water sources.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Once these points were marked, he was able to identify the water source within the cluster that was responsible for the outbreak.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] This was one of the earliest successful uses of a geographic methodology in pinpointing the source of an outbreak in epidemiology.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] While the basic elements of topography and theme existed previously in cartography, Snow's map was unique due to his use of cartographic methods, not only to depict, but also to analyze clusters of geographically dependent phenomena.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The early 20th century saw the development of photozincography, which allowed maps to be split into layers, for example one layer for vegetation and another for water.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] This was particularly used for printing contours – drawing these was a labour-intensive task but having them on a separate layer meant they could be worked on without the other layers to confuse the draughtsman.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] This work was initially drawn on glass plates, but later plastic film was introduced, with the advantages of being lighter, using less storage space and being less brittle, among others.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] When all the layers were finished, they were combined into one image using a large process camera.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Once color printing came in, the layers idea was also used for creating separate printing plates for each color.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] While the use of layers much later became one of the typical features of a contemporary GIS, the photographic process just described is not considered a GIS in itself – as the maps were just images with no database to link them to.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Two additional developments are notable in the early days of GIS: Ian McHarg's publication *Design with Nature* and its map overlay method and the introduction of a street network into the U.S.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Census Bureau's DIME (Dual Independent Map Encoding) system.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The first publication detailing the use of computers to facilitate cartography was written by Waldo Tobler in 1959.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Further computer hardware development spurred by nuclear weapon research led to more widespread general-purpose computer "mapping" applications by the early 1960s.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] In 1963, the world's first true operational GIS was developed in Ottawa, Ontario, Canada, by the federal Department of Forestry and Rural Development.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] A rating classification factor was also added to permit analysis.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] CGIS was an improvement over "computer mapping" applications as it provided capabilities for data storage, overlay, measurement, and digitizing/scanning.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] It supported a national coordinate system that spanned the continent, coded lines as arcs having a true embedded topology and it stored the attribute and locational information in separate files.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] As a result of this, Tomlinson has become known as the "father of GIS", particularly for his use of overlays in promoting the spatial analysis of convergent geographic data.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] CGIS lasted into the 1990s and built a large digital land resource database in Canada.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] It was developed as a mainframe-based system in support of federal and provincial resource planning and management.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Its strength was continent-wide analysis of complex datasets.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The CGIS was never available commercially.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] These programs were the first examples of general-purpose GIS software that was not developed for a particular installation, and was very influential on future commercial software, such as Esri ARC/INFO, released in 1983.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Working in the Harvard Lab, Tom Waugh developed his vector-based Geographic Information Mapping and Manipulation System (GIMMS) software from 1969.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] He returned to the University of Edinburgh and this software was sold commercially from 1973.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] By 1977 it was used at 300 sites worldwide.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] This can be considered the first globally used GIS which anticipated some key characteristics of the Harvard Odyssey system by nearly five years and ARC/INFO by a decade.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] In 1986, Mapping Display and Analysis System (MIDAS), the first desktop GIS product, was released for MS-DOS.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] It was renamed in 1990 to MapInfo for Windows when it was ported to Windows.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] This began the process of moving GIS from the research department into the business environment.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] By the end of the 20th century, the rapid growth in various systems had been consolidated and standardized on relatively few platforms and users were beginning to explore viewing GIS data over the Internet, requiring data format and transfer standards.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] More recently, a growing number of free, open-source GIS packages run on a range of operating systems and can be customized to perform specific tasks.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The major trend of the 21st century has been the integration of GIS capabilities with other Information technology and Internet infrastructure, such as relational databases, cloud computing, software as a service (SaaS), and mobile computing.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Starting in the late 1970s, many software packages have been created specifically for GIS applications.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Esri's ArcGIS, which includes ArcGIS Pro and the legacy software ArcMap, currently dominates the GIS market.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Other examples of GIS include Autodesk and MapInfo Professional and open-source programs such as QGIS, GRASS GIS, MapGuide, and Hadoop-GIS.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] These and other desktop GIS applications include a full suite of capabilities for entering, managing, analyzing, and visualizing geographic data, and are designed to be used on their own.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Starting in the late 1990s with the emergence of the Internet, as computer network technology progressed, GIS infrastructure and data began to move to servers, providing another mechanism for providing GIS capabilities.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] This was facilitated by standalone software installed on a server, similar to other server software such as HTTP servers and relational database management systems, enabling clients to have access to GIS data and processing tools without having to install specialized desktop software.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] These networks are known as distributed GIS.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] This strategy has been extended through the Internet and development of cloud-based GIS platforms such as ArcGIS Online and GIS-specialized software as a service (SAAS).
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The use of the Internet to facilitate distributed GIS is known as Internet GIS.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] An alternative approach is the integration of some or all of these capabilities into other software or information technology architectures.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] One example is a spatial extension to Object-relational database software, which defines a geometry datatype so that spatial data can be stored in relational tables, and extensions to SQL for spatial analysis operations such as overlay.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The core of any GIS is a database that contains representations of geographic phenomena, modeling their *geometry* (location and shape) and their *properties* or *attributes*.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] A GIS database may be stored in a variety of forms, such as a collection of separate data files or a single spatially-enabled relational database.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Collecting and managing these data usually constitutes the bulk of the time and financial resources of a project, far more than other aspects such as analysis and mapping.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] GIS uses spatio-temporal (space-time) location as the key index variable for all other information.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Just as a relational database containing text or numbers can relate many different tables using common key index variables, GIS can relate otherwise unrelated information by using location as the key index variable.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The key is the location and/or extent in space-time.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Any variable that can be located spatially, and increasingly also temporally, can be referenced using a GIS.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Locations or extents in Earth space–time may be recorded as dates/times of occurrence, and x, y, and z coordinates representing, longitude, latitude, and elevation, respectively.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] These GIS coordinates may represent other quantified systems of temporo-spatial reference (for example, film frame number, stream gage station, highway mile-marker, surveyor benchmark, building address, street intersection, entrance gate, water depth sounding, POS or CAD drawing origin/units).
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Related by accurate spatial information, an incredible variety of real-world and projected past or future data can be analyzed, interpreted and represented.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] This key characteristic of GIS has begun to open new avenues of scientific inquiry into behaviors and patterns of real-world information that previously had not been systematically correlated.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] GIS data represents phenomena that exist in the real world, such as roads, land use, elevation, trees, waterways, and states.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The most common types of phenomena that are represented in data can be divided into two conceptualizations: discrete objects (e.g., a house, a road) and continuous fields (e.g., rainfall amount or population density).
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Other types of geographic phenomena, such as events (e.g., location of World War II battles), processes (e.g., extent of suburbanization), and masses (e.g., types of soil in an area) are represented less commonly or indirectly, or are modeled in analysis procedures rather than data.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Traditionally, there are two broad methods used to store data in a GIS for both kinds of abstractions mapping references: raster images and vector.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Points, lines, and polygons represent vector data of mapped location attribute references.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] A new hybrid method of storing data is that of identifying point clouds, which combine three-dimensional points with RGB information at each point, returning a 3D color image.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] GIS thematic maps then are becoming more and more realistically visually descriptive of what they set out to show or determine.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] All of these methods can consume significant time, finances, and other resources.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Survey data can be directly entered into a GIS from digital data collection systems on survey instruments using a technique called coordinate geometry (COGO).
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Positions from a global navigation satellite system (GNSS) like the Global Positioning System can also be collected and then imported into a GIS.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] A current trend in data collection gives users the ability to use field computers with the ability to edit live data using wireless connections or disconnected editing sessions.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The current trend is to use applications available on smartphones and PDAs in the form of mobile GIS.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] This has been enhanced by the availability of low-cost mapping-grade GPS units with decimeter accuracy in real time.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] This eliminates the need to post process, import, and update the data in the office after fieldwork has been collected.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] This includes the ability to incorporate positions collected using a laser rangefinder.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] New technologies also allow users to create maps as well as analysis directly in the field, making projects more efficient and mapping more accurate.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Remotely sensed data also plays an important role in data collection and consist of sensors attached to a platform.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Sensors include cameras, digital scanners and lidar, while platforms usually consist of aircraft and satellites.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] In England in the mid-1990s, hybrid kite/balloons called helikites first pioneered the use of compact airborne digital cameras as airborne geo-information systems.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Aircraft measurement software, accurate to 0.4 mm, was used to link the photographs and measure the ground.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Helikites are inexpensive and gather more accurate data than aircraft.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Helikites can be used over roads, railways and towns where unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) are banned.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Recently, aerial data collection has become more accessible with miniature UAVs and drones.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] For example, the Aeryon Scout was used to map a 50-acre area with a ground sample distance of 1 inch (2.54 cm) in only 12 minutes.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The majority of digital data currently comes from photo interpretation of aerial photographs.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Soft-copy workstations are used to digitize features directly from stereo pairs of digital photographs.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] These systems allow data to be captured in two and three dimensions, with elevations measured directly from a stereo pair using principles of photogrammetry.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Analog aerial photos must be scanned before being entered into a soft-copy system, for high-quality digital cameras this step is skipped.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Satellite remote sensing provides another important source of spatial data.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Here satellites use different sensor packages to passively measure the reflectance from parts of the electromagnetic spectrum or radio waves that were sent out from an active sensor such as radar.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Remote sensing collects raster data that can be further processed using different bands to identify objects and classes of interest, such as land cover.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The most common method of data creation is digitization, where a hard copy map or survey plan is transferred into a digital medium through the use of a CAD program, and geo-referencing capabilities.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] With the wide availability of ortho-rectified imagery (from satellites, aircraft, Helikites and UAVs), heads-up digitizing is becoming the main avenue through which geographic data is extracted.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Heads-up digitizing involves the tracing of geographic data directly on top of the aerial imagery instead of by the traditional method of tracing the geographic form on a separate digitizing tablet (heads-down digitizing).
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Heads-down digitizing, or manual digitizing, uses a special magnetic pen, or stylus, that feeds information into a computer to create an identical, digital map.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Some tablets use a mouse-like tool, called a puck, instead of a stylus.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The puck has a small window with cross-hairs which allows for greater precision and pinpointing map features.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Though heads-up digitizing is more commonly used, heads-down digitizing is still useful for digitizing maps of poor quality.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Existing data printed on paper or PET film maps can be digitized or scanned to produce digital data.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] A digitizer produces vector data as an operator traces points, lines, and polygon boundaries from a map.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Scanning a map results in raster data that could be further processed to produce vector data.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] When data is captured, the user should consider if the data should be captured with either a relative accuracy or absolute accuracy, since this could not only influence how information will be interpreted but also the cost of data capture.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] After entering data into a GIS, the data usually requires editing, to remove errors, or further processing.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] For vector data it must be made "topologically correct" before it can be used for some advanced analysis.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] For example, in a road network, lines must connect with nodes at an intersection.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Errors such as undershoots and overshoots must also be removed.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] For scanned maps, blemishes on the source map may need to be removed from the resulting raster.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] For example, a fleck of dirt might connect two lines that should not be connected.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The earth can be represented by various models, each of which may provide a different set of coordinates (e.g., latitude, longitude, elevation) for any given point on the Earth's surface.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The simplest model is to assume the earth is a perfect sphere.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] As more measurements of the earth have accumulated, the models of the earth have become more sophisticated and more accurate.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] In fact, there are models called datums that apply to different areas of the earth to provide increased accuracy, like North American Datum of 1983 for U.S. measurements, and the World Geodetic System for worldwide measurements.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The latitude and longitude on a map made against a local datum may not be the same as one obtained from a GPS receiver.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Converting coordinates from one datum to another requires a datum transformation such as a Helmert transformation, although in certain situations a simple translation may be sufficient.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] In popular GIS software, data projected in latitude/longitude is often represented as a Geographic coordinate system.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] For example, data in latitude/longitude if the datum is the 'North American Datum of 1983' is denoted by 'GCS North American 1983'.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] While no digital model can be a perfect representation of the real world, it is important that GIS data be of a high quality.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] In keeping with the principle of homomorphism, the data must be close enough to reality so that the results of GIS procedures correctly correspond to the results of real world processes.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] This means that there is no single standard for data quality, because the necessary degree of quality depends on the scale and purpose of the tasks for which it is to be used.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] is the amount of difference between them.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] on 1 April 2020 was 2,304,580; if it was actually 2,310,674, this would be an error and thus a lack of attribute accuracy.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The degree of refinement in a represented value.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] In a quantitative property, this is the number of significant digits in the measured value.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] An imprecise value is vague or ambiguous, including a range of possible values.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] For example, if one were to say that the population of Houston on 1 April 2020 was "about 2.3 million," this statement would be imprecise, but likely accurate because the correct value (and many incorrect values) are included.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] As with accuracy, representations of location, property, and time can all be more or less precise.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] is closely related to precision in maps, as it dictates a desirable level of spatial precision, but is problematic in GIS, where a data set can be shown at a variety of display scales (including scales that would not be appropriate for the quality of the data).
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] A general acknowledgement of the presence of error and imprecision in geographic data.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] This is sometimes used as a collective term for all or most aspects of data quality.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The degree to which an aspect (location, property, or time) of a phenomenon is inherently imprecise, rather than the imprecision being in a measured value.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] are commonly used to manage vagueness in geographic data.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The degree to which a data set represents all of the actual features that it purports to include.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] " is missing some actual streets, it is incomplete.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The most recent point in time at which a data set claims to be an accurate representation of reality.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] This is a concern for the majority of GIS applications, which attempt to represent the world "at present," in which case older data is of lower quality.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The degree to which the representations of the many phenomena in a data set correctly correspond with each other.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] between spatial objects is an especially important aspect of consistency.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] tools such as shortest path would still give correct results.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] methods and other processing tools derives from the quality of input data.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] is a common operation used in many ways in GIS; because it generates estimates of values between known measurements, the results will always be more precise, but less certain (as each estimate has an unknown amount of error).
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The quality of a dataset is very dependent upon its sources, and the methods used to create it.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Land surveyors have been able to provide a high level of positional accuracy using high-end GPS equipment, but GPS locations on the average smartphone are much less accurate.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Common datasets such as digital terrain and aerial imagery are available in a wide variety of levels of quality, especially spatial precision.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Paper maps, which have been digitized for many years as a data source, can also be of widely varying quality.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] A quantitative analysis of maps brings accuracy issues into focus.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The electronic and other equipment used to make measurements for GIS is far more precise than the machines of conventional map analysis.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] All geographical data are inherently inaccurate, and these inaccuracies will propagate through GIS operations in ways that are difficult to predict.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Data restructuring can be performed by a GIS to convert data into different formats.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] For example, a GIS may be used to convert a satellite image map to a vector structure by generating lines around all cells with the same classification, while determining the cell spatial relationships, such as adjacency or inclusion.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] More advanced data processing can occur with image processing, a technique developed in the late 1960s by NASA and the private sector to provide contrast enhancement, false color rendering and a variety of other techniques including use of two dimensional Fourier transforms.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Since digital data is collected and stored in various ways, the two data sources may not be entirely compatible.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] So a GIS must be able to convert geographic data from one structure to another.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] In so doing, the implicit assumptions behind different ontologies and classifications require analysis.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Object ontologies have gained increasing prominence as a consequence of object-oriented programming and sustained work by Barry Smith and co-workers.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Spatial ETL tools provide the data processing functionality of traditional extract, transform, load (ETL) software, but with a primary focus on the ability to manage spatial data.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] They provide GIS users with the ability to translate data between different standards and proprietary formats, whilst geometrically transforming the data en route.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] These tools can come in the form of add-ins to existing wider-purpose software such as spreadsheets.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] GIS spatial analysis is a rapidly changing field, and GIS packages are increasingly including analytical tools as standard built-in facilities, as optional toolsets, as add-ins or 'analysts'.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] In many instances these are provided by the original software suppliers (commercial vendors or collaborative non-commercial development teams), while in other cases facilities have been developed and are provided by third parties.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Furthermore, many products offer software development kits (SDKs), programming languages and language support, scripting facilities and/or special interfaces for developing one's own analytical tools or variants.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The increased availability has created a new dimension to business intelligence termed "spatial intelligence" which, when openly delivered via intranet, democratizes access to geographic and social network data.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Geospatial intelligence, based on GIS spatial analysis, has also become a key element for security.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] GIS as a whole can be described as conversion to a vectorial representation or to any other digitisation process.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Many geographic tasks involve the terrain, the shape of the surface of the earth, such as hydrology, earthworks, and biogeography.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Thus, terrain data is often a core dataset in a GIS, usually in the form of a raster Digital elevation model (DEM) or a Triangulated irregular network (TIN).
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] A variety of tools are available in most GIS software for analyzing terrain, often by creating derivative datasets that represent a specific aspect of the surface.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Most of these are generated using algorithms that are discrete simplifications of vector calculus.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Slope, aspect, and surface curvature in terrain analysis are all derived from neighborhood operations using elevation values of a cell's adjacent neighbours.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Each of these is strongly affected by the level of detail in the terrain data, such as the resolution of a DEM, which should be chosen carefully.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Distance is a key part of solving many geographic tasks, usually due to the friction of distance.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Thus, a wide variety of analysis tools have analyze distance in some form, such as buffers, Voronoi or Thiessen polygons, Cost distance analysis, and network analysis.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] It is difficult to relate wetlands maps to rainfall amounts recorded at different points such as airports, television stations, and schools.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] A GIS, however, can be used to depict two- and three-dimensional characteristics of the Earth's surface, subsurface, and atmosphere from information points.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] For example, a GIS can quickly generate a map with isopleth or contour lines that indicate differing amounts of rainfall.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Such a map can be thought of as a rainfall contour map.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Many sophisticated methods can estimate the characteristics of surfaces from a limited number of point measurements.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] A two-dimensional contour map created from the surface modeling of rainfall point measurements may be overlaid and analyzed with any other map in a GIS covering the same area.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] This GIS derived map can then provide additional information – such as the viability of water power potential as a renewable energy source.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Similarly, GIS can be used to compare other renewable energy resources to find the best geographic potential for a region.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Additionally, from a series of three-dimensional points, or digital elevation model, isopleth lines representing elevation contours can be generated, along with slope analysis, shaded relief, and other elevation products.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Watersheds can be easily defined for any given reach, by computing all of the areas contiguous and uphill from any given point of interest.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Similarly, an expected thalweg of where surface water would want to travel in intermittent and permanent streams can be computed from elevation data in the GIS.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] A GIS can recognize and analyze the spatial relationships that exist within digitally stored spatial data.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] These topological relationships allow complex spatial modelling and analysis to be performed.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Topological relationships between geometric entities traditionally include adjacency (what adjoins what), containment (what encloses what), and proximity (how close something is to something else).
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Geometric networks are linear networks of objects that can be used to represent interconnected features, and to perform special spatial analysis on them.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] A geometric network is composed of edges, which are connected at junction points, similar to graphs in mathematics and computer science.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Just like graphs, networks can have weight and flow assigned to its edges, which can be used to represent various interconnected features more accurately.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Geometric networks are often used to model road networks and public utility networks, such as electric, gas, and water networks.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Network modeling is also commonly employed in transportation planning, hydrology modeling, and infrastructure modeling.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Dana Tomlin coined the term *cartographic modeling* in his PhD dissertation (1983); he later used it in the title of his book, *Geographic Information Systems and Cartographic Modeling* (1990).
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Cartographic modeling refers to a process where several thematic layers of the same area are produced, processed, and analyzed.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Tomlin used raster layers, but the overlay method (see below) can be used more generally.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Operations on map layers can be combined into algorithms, and eventually into simulation or optimization models.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The combination of several spatial datasets (points, lines, or polygons) creates a new output vector dataset, visually similar to stacking several maps of the same region.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] These overlays are similar to mathematical Venn diagram overlays.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] A union overlay combines the geographic features and attribute tables of both inputs into a single new output.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] An intersect overlay defines the area where both inputs overlap and retains a set of attribute fields for each.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] A symmetric difference overlay defines an output area that includes the total area of both inputs except for the overlapping area.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Data extraction is a GIS process similar to vector overlay, though it can be used in either vector or raster data analysis.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Rather than combining the properties and features of both datasets, data extraction involves using a "clip" or "mask" to extract the features of one data set that fall within the spatial extent of another dataset.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] In raster data analysis, the overlay of datasets is accomplished through a process known as "local operation on multiple rasters" or "map algebra", through a function that combines the values of each raster's matrix.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] This function may weigh some inputs more than others through use of an "index model" that reflects the influence of various factors upon a geographic phenomenon.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Geostatistics is a branch of statistics that deals with field data, spatial data with a continuous index.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] It provides methods to model spatial correlation, and predict values at arbitrary locations (interpolation).
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] When phenomena are measured, the observation methods dictate the accuracy of any subsequent analysis.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Due to the nature of the data (e.g. traffic patterns in an urban environment; weather patterns over the Pacific Ocean), a constant or dynamic degree of precision is always lost in the measurement.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] This loss of precision is determined from the scale and distribution of the data collection.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] To determine the statistical relevance of the analysis, an average is determined so that points (gradients) outside of any immediate measurement can be included to determine their predicted behavior.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] This is due to the limitations of the applied statistic and data collection methods, and interpolation is required to predict the behavior of particles, points, and locations that are not directly measurable.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Interpolation is the process by which a surface is created, usually a raster dataset, through the input of data collected at a number of sample points.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] There are several forms of interpolation, each which treats the data differently, depending on the properties of the data set.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] In comparing interpolation methods, the first consideration should be whether or not the source data will change (exact or approximate).
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Next is whether the method is subjective, a human interpretation, or objective.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Then there is the nature of transitions between points: are they abrupt or gradual.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Finally, there is whether a method is global (it uses the entire data set to form the model), or local where an algorithm is repeated for a small section of terrain.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Interpolation is a justified measurement because of a spatial autocorrelation principle that recognizes that data collected at any position will have a great similarity to, or influence of those locations within its immediate vicinity.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Digital elevation models, triangulated irregular networks, edge-finding algorithms, Thiessen polygons, Fourier analysis, (weighted) moving averages, inverse distance weighting, kriging, spline, and trend surface analysis are all mathematical methods to produce interpolative data.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Geocoding is interpolating spatial locations (X,Y coordinates) from street addresses or any other spatially referenced data such as ZIP Codes, parcel lots and address locations.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] A reference theme is required to geocode individual addresses, such as a road centerline file with address ranges.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The individual address locations have historically been interpolated, or estimated, by examining address ranges along a road segment.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] These are usually provided in the form of a table or database.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The software will then place a dot approximately where that address belongs along the segment of centerline.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] For example, an address point of 500 will be at the midpoint of a line segment that starts with address 1 and ends with address 1,000.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Geocoding can also be applied against actual parcel data, typically from municipal tax maps.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] In this case, the result of the geocoding will be an actually positioned space as opposed to an interpolated point.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] This approach is being increasingly used to provide more precise location information.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Reverse geocoding is the process of returning an estimated street address number as it relates to a given coordinate.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] For example, a user can click on a road centerline theme (thus providing a coordinate) and have information returned that reflects the estimated house number.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] This house number is interpolated from a range assigned to that road segment.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] If the user clicks at the midpoint of a segment that starts with address 1 and ends with 100, the returned value will be somewhere near 50.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Note that reverse geocoding does not return actual addresses, only estimates of what should be there based on the predetermined range.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Coupled with GIS, multi-criteria decision analysis methods support decision-makers in analysing a set of alternative spatial solutions, such as the most likely ecological habitat for restoration, against multiple criteria, such as vegetation cover or roads.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] MCDA uses decision rules to aggregate the criteria, which allows the alternative solutions to be ranked or prioritised.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] GIS MCDA may reduce costs and time involved in identifying potential restoration sites.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] GIS or spatial data mining is the application of data mining methods to spatial data.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Data mining, which is the partially automated search for hidden patterns in large databases, offers great potential benefits for applied GIS-based decision making.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Typical applications include environmental monitoring.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] A characteristic of such applications is that spatial correlation between data measurements require the use of specialized algorithms for more efficient data analysis.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] GIS-based spatial modeling has increasingly been combined with machine learning techniques to identify and forecast regional inequities in health and social outcomes, including healthcare access and insurance enrollment.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Cartography is the design and production of maps, or visual representations of spatial data.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The vast majority of modern cartography is done with the help of computers, usually using GIS but production of quality cartography is also achieved by importing layers into a design program to refine it.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Most GIS software gives the user substantial control over the appearance of the data.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] First, it produces graphics on the screen or on paper that convey the results of analysis to the people who make decisions about resources.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Wall maps and other graphics can be generated, allowing the viewer to visualize and thereby understand the results of analyses or simulations of potential events.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Web Map Servers facilitate distribution of generated maps through web browsers using various implementations of web-based application programming interfaces (AJAX, Java, Flash, etc.).
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Second, other database information can be generated for further analysis or use.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] An example would be a list of all addresses within one mile (1.6 km) of a toxic spill.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] An archeochrome is a new way of displaying spatial data.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] It is a thematic on a 3D map that is applied to a specific building or a part of a building.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] It is suited to the visual display of heat-loss data.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Traditional maps are abstractions of the real world, a sampling of important elements portrayed on a sheet of paper with symbols to represent physical objects.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] People who use maps must interpret these symbols.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Topographic maps show the shape of land surface with contour lines or with shaded relief.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Today, graphic display techniques such as shading based on altitude in a GIS can make relationships among map elements visible, heightening one's ability to extract and analyze information.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] For example, two types of data were combined in a GIS to produce a perspective view of a portion of San Mateo County, California.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] A GIS was used to register and combine the two images to render the three-dimensional perspective view looking down the San Andreas Fault, using the Thematic Mapper image pixels, but shaded using the elevation of the landforms.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] The GIS display depends on the viewing point of the observer and time of day of the display, to properly render the shadows created by the sun's rays at that latitude, longitude, and time of day.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] There has been a proliferation of free-to-use and easily accessible mapping software such as the proprietary web applications Google Maps and Bing Maps, as well as the free and open-source alternative OpenStreetMap.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] These services give the public access to huge amounts of geographic data, perceived by many users to be as trustworthy and usable as professional information.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] For example, during the COVID-19 pandemic, web maps hosted on dashboards were used to rapidly disseminate case data to the general public.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Some of them, like Google Maps and OpenLayers, expose an application programming interface (API) that enable users to create custom applications.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] These toolkits commonly offer street maps, aerial/satellite imagery, geocoding, searches, and routing functionality.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Web mapping has also uncovered the potential of crowdsourcing geodata in projects like OpenStreetMap, which is a collaborative project to create a free editable map of the world.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] These mashup projects have been proven to provide a high level of value and benefit to end users outside that possible through traditional geographic information.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] Web mapping allows for the creation and distribution of maps by people without proper cartographic training.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p01] This has led to maps that ignore cartographic conventions and are potentially misleading, with one study finding that more than half of United States state government COVID-19 dashboards did not follow these conventions.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Since its origin in the 1960s, GIS has been used in an ever-increasing range of applications, corroborating the widespread importance of location and aided by the continuing reduction in the barriers to adopting geospatial technology.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] The implementation of a GIS is often driven by jurisdictional (such as a city), purpose, or application requirements.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Generally, a GIS implementation may be custom-designed for an organization.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Hence, a GIS deployment developed for an application, jurisdiction, enterprise, or purpose may not be necessarily interoperable or compatible with a GIS that has been developed for some other application, jurisdiction, enterprise, or purpose.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS is also used in digital marketing and SEO for audience segmentation based on location.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Geographic Information Systems (GIS) has become an integral part of aquatic science and limnology.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Features associated with water are thus ever-changing.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] To be able to keep up with these changes, technological advancements have given scientists methods to enhance all aspects of scientific investigation, from satellite tracking of wildlife to computer mapping of habitats.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Agencies like the US Geological Survey, US Fish and Wildlife Service as well as other federal and state agencies are utilizing GIS to aid in their conservation efforts.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS has been applied to the long-term monitoring of shoreline change and coastal erosion, integrating historical aerial photography, satellite imagery and GPS surveys to quantify retreat rates and assess coastal vulnerability.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] A geographic information system (GIS) consists of integrated computer hardware and software that store, manage, analyze, edit, output, and visualize geographic data.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Geospatial disaster response uses geospatial data and tools to help emergency responders, land managers, and scientists respond to disasters.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Geospatial data can help save lives, reduce damage, and improve communication.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] In the United States, FEMA's Response Geospatial Office is responsible for the agency's capture, analysis and development of GIS products to enhance situational awareness and enable expeditions and effective decision making.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] The RGO's mission is to support decision makers in understanding the size, scope, and extent of disaster impacts so they can deliver resources to the communities most in need.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Geographic information system (GIS) is a commonly used tool for environmental management, modelling and planning.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] As simply defined by Michael Goodchild, GIS is as "a computer system for handling geographic information in a digital form".
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] In recent years it has played an integral role in participatory, collaborative and open data philosophies.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Social and technological evolutions have elevated *digital* and *environmental* agendas to the forefront of public policy, the global media and the private sector.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS in environmental contamination is the use of GIS software to map and analyze contaminants on Earth, including soil contamination, water pollution, and air pollution.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Various GIS methods are used to conduct spatial analysis of pollutants to, identify, monitor, and assess them.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS can use other technologies to advance their process of analysis, including remote sensing, LIDAR, GeoAI, and WebGIS.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] One method includes spatial interpolation, which allows for a more efficient approach to remediation and monitoring of soil and water contaminants.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Contamination by metals and other contaminants has become a significant environmental problem after industrialization across many parts of the world.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] As a result, environmental agencies are placed in charge of remediating, monitoring, and mitigating the soil contamination sites.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS is used to monitor sites for metal contaminants on Earth to identify high-risk sites where remediation and monitoring are needed.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] A geological map or geologic map is a special-purpose map made to show various geological features.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Rock units or geologic strata are shown by color or symbols.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Bedding planes and structural features such as faults, folds, are shown with strike and dip or trend and plunge symbols which give three-dimensional orientations features.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Geological mapping is an interpretive process involving multiple types of information, from analytical data to personal observation, all synthesized and recorded by the geologist.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Geologic observations have traditionally been recorded on paper, whether on standardized note cards, in a notebook, or on a map.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] In geology, GIS is increasingly used for the assessment and forecasting of mineral deposits, particularly for commonly occurring mineral resources (COMR) such as construction sands, clays, and peat.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Unlike the dense and uniformly distributed borehole data typical of oil and gas exploration, COMR exploration often relies on sparse and unevenly distributed datasets.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] This requires specialized GIS algorithms, for instance, those based on Voronoi diagrams, to create three-dimensional geological models from incomplete information.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Beyond modeling, GIS enables a comprehensive evaluation by integrating geological and industrial parameters—such as overburden ratio and deposit thickness—with land-use data to classify and rank potential mining sites based on their economic and environmental acceptability.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] A case study of this integrated approach was demonstrated for the Brest region in Belarus, where a regional digital model was created to forecast and evaluate new non-metallic mineral deposits, considering both geological constraints and land-use regulations for open-pit mining development.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Geographic information systems (GIS) play a constantly evolving role in geospatial intelligence (GEOINT) and United States national security.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] These technologies allow a user to efficiently manage, analyze, and produce geospatial data, to combine GEOINT with other forms of intelligence collection, and to perform highly developed analysis and visual production of geospatial data.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Therefore, GIS produces up-to-date and more reliable GEOINT to reduce uncertainty for a decisionmaker.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Since GIS programs are Web-enabled, a user can constantly work with a decision maker to solve their GEOINT and national security related problems from anywhere in the world.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] There are many types of GIS software used in GEOINT and national security, such as Google Earth, ERDAS IMAGINE, GeoNetwork opensource, and Esri ArcGIS.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] A historical geographic information system (also written as historical GIS or HGIS) is a geographic information system that may display, store and analyze data of past geographies and track changes in time.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] The use of digital maps generated by GIS has also influenced the development of an academic field known as spatial humanities.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Geographic information systems (GISs) have become a useful and important tool in the field of hydrology to study and manage Earth's water resources.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Climate change and greater demands on water resources require a more knowledgeable disposition of arguably one of our most vital resources.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Because water in its occurrence varies spatially and temporally throughout the hydrologic cycle, its study using GIS is especially practical.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Whereas previous GIS systems were mostly static in their geospatial representation of hydrologic features, GIS platforms are becoming increasingly dynamic, narrowing the gap between historical data and current hydrologic reality.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Participatory GIS (PGIS) or public participation geographic information system (PPGIS) is a participatory approach to spatial planning and spatial information and communications management.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Geographic information systems (GISs) and geographic information science (GIScience) combine computer-mapping capabilities with additional database management and data analysis tools.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Commercial GIS systems are very powerful and have touched many applications and industries, including environmental science, urban planning, agricultural applications, and others.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Traditional knowledge Geographic Information Systems (GIS) is a toolset of systems designed to document and utilize traditional knowledge from communities around the world.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Traditional knowledge GIS differ from ordinary cognitive maps in that they express environmental and spiritual relationships among real and conceptual entities.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] This toolset focuses on cultural preservation, land rights disputes, natural resource management, and economic development.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] The Open Geospatial Consortium (OGC) is an international industry consortium of 384 companies, government agencies, universities, and individuals participating in a consensus process to develop publicly available geoprocessing specifications.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Open Geospatial Consortium protocols include Web Map Service, and Web Feature Service.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS products are broken down by the OGC into two categories, based on how completely and accurately the software follows the OGC specifications.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] The condition of the Earth's surface, atmosphere, and subsurface can be examined by feeding satellite data into a GIS.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS technology gives researchers the ability to examine the variations in Earth processes over days, months, and years through the use of cartographic visualizations.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] As an example, the changes in vegetation vigor through a growing season can be animated to determine when drought was most extensive in a particular region.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] The resulting graphic represents a rough measure of plant health.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Working with two variables over time would then allow researchers to detect regional differences in the lag between a decline in rainfall and its effect on vegetation.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS technology and the availability of digital data on regional and global scales enable such analyses.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] The satellite sensor output used to generate a vegetation graphic is produced for example by the advanced very-high-resolution radiometer (AVHRR).
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] This sensor system detects the amounts of energy reflected from the Earth's surface across various bands of the spectrum for surface areas of about 1 km2 (0.39 sq mi).
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] The satellite sensor produces images of a particular location on the Earth twice a day.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] AVHRR and more recently the moderate-resolution imaging spectroradiometer (MODIS) are only two of many sensor systems used for Earth surface analysis.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] In addition to the integration of time in environmental studies, GIS is also being explored for its ability to track and model the progress of humans throughout their daily routines.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] A concrete example of progress in this area is the recent release of time-specific population data by the U.S.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] In this data set, the populations of cities are shown for daytime and evening hours highlighting the pattern of concentration and dispersion generated by North American commuting patterns.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] The manipulation and generation of data required to produce this data would not have been possible without GIS.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Using models to project the data held by a GIS forward in time have enabled planners to test policy decisions using spatial decision support systems.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Tools and technologies emerging from the World Wide Web Consortium's Semantic Web are proving useful for data integration problems in information systems.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Correspondingly, such technologies have been proposed as a means to facilitate interoperability and data reuse among GIS applications and also to enable new analysis mechanisms.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Ontologies are a key component of this semantic approach as they allow a formal, machine-readable specification of the concepts and relationships in a given domain.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] This in turn allows a GIS to focus on the intended meaning of data rather than its syntax or structure.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Tentative ontologies have been developed in areas related to GIS applications, for example the hydrology ontology developed by the Ordnance Survey in the United Kingdom and the SWEET ontologies developed by NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Also, simpler ontologies and semantic metadata standards are being proposed by the W3C Geo Incubator Group to represent geospatial data on the web.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Recent research results in this area can be seen in the International Conference on Geospatial Semantics and the Terra Cognita – Directions to the Geospatial Semantic Web workshop at the International Semantic Web Conference.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] With the popularization of GIS in decision making, scholars have begun to scrutinize the social and political implications of GIS.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS can also be misused to distort reality for individual and political gain.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS technologies played a central role during the COVID-19 pandemic by enabling public health agencies and researchers to visualize and monitor disease spread in real time.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] The *Johns Hopkins University COVID-19 Dashboard* became one of the most widely cited GIS applications, demonstrating how web-based spatial data can inform policy and public awareness.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] It has been argued that the production, distribution, use, and representation of geographic information are largely related with the social context and has the potential to increase citizen trust in government.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Other related topics include discussion on copyright, privacy, and censorship.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] A more optimistic social approach to GIS adoption is to use it as a tool for public participation.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] At the end of the 20th century, GIS began to be recognized as tools that could be used in the classroom.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS seems to provide many advantages in teaching geography because it allows for analysis based on real geographic data and also helps raise research questions from teachers and students in the classroom.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] It also contributes to improvement in learning by developing spatial and geographical thinking and, in many cases, student motivation.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Courses in GIS are also offered by educational institutions.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS is proven as an organization-wide, enterprise and enduring technology that continues to change how local government operates.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS has been an important tool in archaeology since the early 1990s.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Surveys and documentation are important to preservation and archaeology, and GIS makes this research and fieldwork efficient and precise.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS is also used to help manage the conservation of cultural heritage sites.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS helps conservation organizations monitor the impacts of development, conflict, and climate change on archaeological and other cultural resources.
[src:precision-agriculture/geographic-information-system-p02] Some public agencies use GIS software to assess the potential impacts of construction and other development and use these assessments in permitting and mitigation processes.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] officer operates the Global Positioning System in 2022.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The **Global Positioning System** (**GPS**) is a satellite-based hyperbolic navigation system owned by the United States Space Force and operated by Mission Delta 31.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] It is one of the global navigation satellite systems (GNSS) that provide geolocation and time information to a GPS receiver anywhere on or near the Earth where signal quality permits.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] It does not require the user to transmit any data, and operates independently of any telephone or Internet reception, though these technologies can enhance the usefulness of the GPS positioning information.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] It provides critical positioning capabilities to military, civil, and commercial users around the world.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Although the United States government created, controls, and maintains GPS, it is freely accessible to anyone with a GPS receiver.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The prototype spacecraft was launched in 1978 and the full constellation of 24 satellites became operational in 1993.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] As civilian GPS usage grew, there was increasing pressure to remove this error.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The SA system was temporarily disabled during the Gulf War, as a shortage of military GPS units meant that many US soldiers were using civilian GPS units sent from home.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] In the 1990s, differential GPS systems from the US Coast Guard, Federal Aviation Administration, and similar agencies in other countries began to broadcast local GPS corrections, reducing the effect of both SA degradation and atmospheric effects (that military receivers also corrected for).
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The U.S. military had also developed methods to perform local GPS jamming, meaning that the ability to globally degrade the system was no longer necessary.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] As a result, United States President Bill Clinton signed a bill ordering that Selective Availability be disabled on May 1, 2000; and, in 2007, the US government announced that the next generation of GPS satellites would not include the feature.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Advances in technology and new demands on the existing system have led to efforts to modernize GPS and implement the next generation of GPS Block III satellites and Next Generation Operational Control System (OCX) which was authorized by the U.S.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] When Selective Availability was discontinued, GPS was accurate to about 5 meters (16 ft).
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] GPS receivers that use the L5 band have much higher accuracy of 30 centimeters (12 in), while those for high-end applications such as engineering and land surveying are accurate to within 2 cm (3⁄4 in) and can even provide sub-millimeter accuracy with long-term measurements.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Consumer devices such as smartphones can be accurate to 4.9 m (16 ft) or better when used with assistive services like Wi-Fi positioning.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] As of March 2026, 21 GPS satellites broadcast L5 signals, which are considered pre-operational prior to being broadcast by a full complement of 24 satellites in 2027.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The GPS project was launched in the United States in 1973 to overcome the limitations of previous navigation systems, combining ideas from several predecessors, including classified engineering design studies from the 1960s.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Department of Defense developed the system, which originally used 24 satellites, for use by the United States military, and became fully operational in 1993.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Civilian use was allowed from the 1980s.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Easton of the Naval Research Laboratory, Ivan A.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Getting of The Aerospace Corporation, and Bradford Parkinson of the Applied Physics Laboratory are credited with inventing it.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The work of Gladys West of the Ballistic Sciences Branch at Dahlgren Naval Proving Ground on the creation of the mathematical geodetic Earth model is credited as instrumental in the development of computational techniques for detecting satellite positions with the precision needed for GPS.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The design of GPS is based partly on similar ground-based radio-navigation systems, such as LORAN and the Decca Navigator System, developed in the early 1940s.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] In 1955, Friedwardt Winterberg proposed a test of general relativity—detecting time slowing in a strong gravitational field using accurate atomic clocks placed in orbit inside artificial satellites.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Special and general relativity predicted that the clocks on GPS satellites, as observed by those on Earth, run 38 microseconds faster per day than those on the Earth.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The design of GPS corrects for this difference.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] When the Soviet Union launched its first artificial satellite (Sputnik 1) in 1957, two American physicists, William Guier and George Weiffenbach, at Johns Hopkins University's Applied Physics Laboratory (APL) monitored its radio transmissions.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Within hours they realized that, because of the Doppler effect, they could pinpoint where the satellite was along its orbit.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The Director of the APL gave them access to their UNIVAC I computer to perform the heavy calculations required.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Early the next year, Frank McClure, the deputy director of the APL, asked Guier and Weiffenbach to investigate the inverse problem: pinpointing the user's location, given the satellite's.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] (At the time, the Navy was developing the submarine-launched Polaris missile, which required them to know the submarine's location.) This led them and APL to develop the TRANSIT system.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] In 1959, ARPA (renamed DARPA in 1972) also played a role in TRANSIT.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] TRANSIT was first successfully tested in 1960.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] It used a constellation of five satellites and could provide a navigational fix approximately once per hour.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Navy developed the Timation satellite, which proved the feasibility of placing accurate clocks in space, a technology required for GPS.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] In the 1970s, the ground-based OMEGA navigation system, based on phase comparison of signal transmission from pairs of stations, became the first worldwide radio navigation system.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Limitations of these systems drove the need for a more universal navigation solution with greater accuracy.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Although there were wide needs for accurate navigation in military and civilian sectors, almost none of those was seen as justification for the billions of dollars it would cost in research, development, deployment, and operation of a constellation of navigation satellites.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] During the Cold War arms race, the nuclear threat to the existence of the United States was the one need that did justify this cost in the view of the United States Congress.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] This deterrent effect is why GPS was funded.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] It is also the reason for the ultra-secrecy at that time.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The nuclear triad consisted of the United States Navy's submarine-launched ballistic missiles (SLBMs) along with United States Air Force (USAF) strategic bombers and intercontinental ballistic missiles (ICBMs).
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Considered vital to the nuclear deterrence posture, accurate determination of the SLBM launch position was a force multiplier.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Precise navigation would enable United States ballistic missile submarines to get an accurate fix of their positions before they launched their SLBMs.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The USAF, with two-thirds of the nuclear triad, also had requirements for a more accurate and reliable navigation system.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Air Force were developing their own technologies in parallel to solve what was essentially the same problem.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] To increase the survivability of ICBMs, there was a proposal to use mobile launch platforms (comparable to the Soviet SS-24 and SS-25) and so the need to fix the launch position had similarity to the SLBM situation.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] In 1960, the Air Force proposed a radio-navigation system called MOSAIC (Mobile System for Accurate ICBM Control) that was essentially a 3-D LORAN System.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] A follow-on study, Project 57, was performed in 1963 and it was "in this study that the GPS concept was born".
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] That same year, the concept was pursued as Project 621B, which had "many of the attributes that you now see in GPS" and promised increased accuracy for U.S.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Updates from the Navy TRANSIT system were too slow for the high speeds of Air Force operation.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The Naval Research Laboratory (NRL) continued making advances with their Timation (Time Navigation) satellites, first launched in 1967, second launched in 1969, with the third in 1974 carrying the first atomic clock into orbit and the fourth launched in 1977.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Another important predecessor to GPS came from a different branch of the United States military.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] In 1964, the United States Army orbited its first Sequential Collation of Range (SECOR) satellite used for geodetic surveying.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The SECOR system included three ground-based transmitters at known locations that would send signals to the satellite transponder in orbit.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] A fourth ground-based station, at an undetermined position, could then use those signals to fix its location precisely.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The last SECOR satellite was launched in 1969.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] With these parallel developments in the 1960s, a superior system could be developed by synthesizing the best technologies from 621B, Transit, Timation, and SECOR in a multi-service program.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Satellite orbital position errors, induced by variations in the gravity field and radar refraction among others, had to be resolved.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Jury of Pan Am Aerospace Division in Florida from 1970 to 1973, used real-time data assimilation and recursive estimation to do so, reducing systematic and residual errors to a manageable level to permit accurate navigation.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] During Labor Day weekend in 1973, a meeting of about twelve military officers at the Pentagon discussed the creation of a *Defense Navigation Satellite System (DNSS)*.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] It was at this meeting that the real synthesis that became GPS was created.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Later that year, the DNSS program was named *Navstar.* The name *Navstar* was not an acronym, but was chosen simply as a nice-sounding word.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] With the individual satellites being associated with the name Navstar (as with the predecessors Transit and Timation), a more fully encompassing name was used to identify the constellation of Navstar satellites, *Navstar-GPS*.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Ten "Block I" prototype satellites were launched between 1978 and 1985 (an additional unit was destroyed in a launch failure).
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The effect of the ionosphere on radio transmission was investigated in a geophysics laboratory of Air Force Cambridge Research Laboratory, renamed to Air Force Geophysical Research Lab (AFGRL) in 1974.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] AFGRL developed the Klobuchar model for computing ionospheric corrections to GPS location.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Of note is work done by Australian space scientist Elizabeth Essex-Cohen at AFGRL in 1974.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] She was concerned with the curving of the paths of radio waves (atmospheric refraction) traversing the ionosphere from Navstar satellites.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The first Block II satellite was launched on February 14, 1989, and the 24th satellite was launched in 1994.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The GPS program cost at this point, not including the cost of the user equipment but including the costs of the satellite launches, has been estimated at US$5 billion (equivalent to $11 billion in 2025).
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Initially, the highest-quality signal was reserved for military use, and the signal available for civilian use was intentionally degraded, in a policy known as Selective Availability.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] President Bill Clinton signing a policy directive to turn off Selective Availability to provide the same accuracy to civilians that was afforded to the military.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Secretary of Defense, William Perry, in view of the widespread growth of differential GPS services by private industry to improve civilian accuracy.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Moreover, the U.S. military was developing technologies to deny GPS service to potential adversaries on a regional basis.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Selective Availability was removed from the GPS architecture beginning with GPS-III.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Since its deployment, the U.S. has implemented several improvements to the GPS service, including new signals for civil use and increased accuracy and integrity for all users, all the while maintaining compatibility with existing GPS equipment.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Modernization of the satellite system has been an ongoing initiative by the U.S.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Department of Defense through a series of satellite acquisitions to meet the growing needs of the military, civilians, and the commercial market.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] As of early 2015, high-quality Standard Positioning Service (SPS) GPS receivers provided horizontal accuracy of better than 3.5 meters (11 ft), although many factors such as receiver and antenna quality and atmospheric issues can affect this accuracy.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] GPS is owned and operated by the United States government as a national resource.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The Department of Defense is the steward of GPS.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The *Interagency GPS Executive Board (IGEB)* oversaw GPS policy matters from 1996 to 2004.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] After that, the National Space-Based Positioning, Navigation and Timing Executive Committee was established by presidential directive in 2004 to advise and coordinate federal departments and agencies on matters concerning the GPS and related systems.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The executive committee is chaired jointly by the Deputy Secretaries of Defense and Transportation.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Its membership includes equivalent-level officials from the Departments of State, Commerce, and Homeland Security, the Joint Chiefs of Staff and NASA.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Components of the executive office of the president participate as observers to the executive committee, and the FCC chairman participates as a liaison.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] On February 10, 1993, the National Aeronautic Association selected the GPS Team as winners of the 1992 Robert J.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Collier Trophy, the US's most prestigious aviation award.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] This team combines researchers from the Naval Research Laboratory, the U.S.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Air Force, the Aerospace Corporation, Rockwell International Corporation, and IBM Federal Systems Company.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The citation honors them "for the most significant development for safe and efficient navigation and surveillance of air and spacecraft since the introduction of radio navigation 50 years ago".
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Easton received the National Medal of Technology on February 13, 2006.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Air Force Space and Missile Pioneers Hall of Fame at Lackland A.F.B., San Antonio, Texas, March 2, 2010, for his role in space technology development and the engineering design concept of GPS conducted as part of Project 621B.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] In 1998, GPS technology was inducted into the Space Foundation Space Technology Hall of Fame.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] On October 4, 2011, the International Astronautical Federation (IAF) awarded the Global Positioning System (GPS) its 60th Anniversary Award, nominated by IAF member, the American Institute for Aeronautics and Astronautics (AIAA).
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The IAF Honors and Awards Committee recognized the uniqueness of the GPS program and the exemplary role it has played in building international collaboration for the benefit of humanity.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] On December 6, 2018, Gladys West was inducted into the Air Force Space and Missile Pioneers Hall of Fame in recognition of her work on an extremely accurate geodetic Earth model, which was ultimately used to determine the orbit of the GPS constellation.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The GPS satellites carry very stable atomic clocks that are synchronized with one another and with the reference atomic clocks at the ground control stations; any drift of the clocks aboard the satellites from the reference time maintained on the ground stations is corrected regularly.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Since the speed of radio waves (speed of light) is constant and independent of the satellite speed, the time delay between when the satellite transmits a signal and the ground station receives it is proportional to the distance from the satellite to the ground station.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] With the distance information collected from multiple ground stations, the location coordinates of any satellite at any time can be calculated with great precision.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Each GPS satellite carries an accurate record of its own position and time, and broadcasts that data continuously.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Conceptually, the receiver measures the TOAs (according to its own clock) of four satellite signals.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] From the TOAs and the TOTs, the receiver forms four time of flight (TOF) values, which are (given the speed of light) approximately equivalent to receiver-satellite ranges plus time difference between the receiver and GPS satellites multiplied by speed of light, which are called pseudo-ranges.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The receiver then computes its three-dimensional position and clock deviation from the four TOFs.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] In practice the receiver position (in three dimensional Cartesian coordinates with origin at the Earth's center) and the offset of the receiver clock relative to the GPS time are computed simultaneously, using the navigation equations to process the TOFs.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The receiver's Earth-centered solution location is usually converted to latitude, longitude and height relative to an ellipsoidal Earth model.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The height may then be further converted to height relative to the geoid, which is essentially mean sea level.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] These coordinates may be displayed, such as on a moving map display, or recorded or used by some other system, such as a vehicle guidance system.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] As of 2025, these core principles are being enhanced by the ongoing modernization of the GPS constellation with the introduction of GPS III and GPS IIIF satellites.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] These next-generation satellites feature more advanced atomic clocks for even greater timekeeping accuracy and broadcast more powerful, secure, and interoperable signals (such as L1C, L2C, and L5).
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] This improves the precision of the time-of-flight (TOF) measurements and provides better resistance to signal interference, enhancing the reliability of the position calculation for all users.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Although usually not formed explicitly in the receiver processing, the conceptual time differences of arrival (TDOAs) define the measurement geometry.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Each TDOA corresponds to a hyperboloid of revolution (see Multilateration).
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The line connecting the two satellites involved (and its extensions) forms the axis of the hyperboloid.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The receiver is located at the point where three hyperboloids intersect.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] It is sometimes incorrectly said that the user location is at the intersection of three spheres.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] While simpler to visualize, this is the case only if the receiver has a clock synchronized with the satellite clocks (i.e., the receiver measures true ranges to the satellites rather than range differences).
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] There are marked performance benefits to the user carrying a clock synchronized with the satellites.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Foremost is that only three satellites are needed to compute a position solution.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] If it were an essential part of the GPS concept that all users needed to carry a synchronized clock, a smaller number of satellites could be deployed, but the cost and complexity of the user equipment would increase.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The description above is representative of a receiver start-up situation.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Most receivers have a track algorithm, sometimes called a *tracker*, that combines sets of satellite measurements collected at different times—in effect, taking advantage of the fact that successive receiver positions are usually close to each other.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] After a set of measurements is processed, the tracker predicts the receiver location corresponding to the next set of satellite measurements.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] When the new measurements are collected, the receiver uses a weighting scheme to combine the new measurements with the tracker prediction.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] In general, a tracker can (a) improve receiver position and time accuracy, (b) reject bad measurements, and (c) estimate receiver speed and direction.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The disadvantage of a tracker is that changes in speed or direction can be computed only with a delay, and that derived direction becomes inaccurate when the distance traveled between two position measurements drops below or near the random error of position measurement.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] GPS units can use measurements of the Doppler shift of the signals received to compute velocity accurately.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] More advanced navigation systems use additional sensors like a compass or an inertial navigation system to complement GPS.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] GPS requires four or more satellites to be visible for accurate navigation.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The solution of the navigation equations gives the position of the receiver along with the difference between the time kept by the receiver's on-board clock and the true time-of-day, thereby eliminating the need for a more precise and possibly impractical receiver based clock.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Applications for GPS such as time transfer, traffic signal timing, and synchronization of cell phone base stations, make use of this cheap and highly accurate timing.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Some GPS applications use this time for display, or, other than for the basic position calculations, do not use it at all.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Although four satellites are required for normal operation, fewer apply in special cases.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] If one variable is already known, a receiver can determine its position using only three satellites.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] For example, a ship on the open ocean usually has a known elevation close to 0 m, and the elevation of an aircraft may be known.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Some GPS receivers may use additional clues or assumptions such as reusing the last known altitude, dead reckoning, inertial navigation, or including information from the vehicle computer, to give a (possibly degraded) position when fewer than four satellites are visible.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The current GPS consists of three major segments.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] These are the space segment, a control segment, and a user segment.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Space Force develops, maintains, and operates the space and control segments.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] GPS satellites broadcast signals from space, and each GPS receiver uses these signals to calculate its three-dimensional location (latitude, longitude, and altitude) and the current time.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The space segment (SS) is composed of 24 to 32 satellites, or Space Vehicles (SV), in medium Earth orbit, and also includes the payload adapters to the boosters required to launch them into orbit.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The GPS design originally called for 24 SVs, eight each in three approximately circular orbits, but this was modified to six orbital planes with four satellites each.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The six orbit planes have approximately 55° inclination (tilt relative to the Earth's equator) and are separated by 60° right ascension of the ascending node (angle along the equator from a reference point to the orbit's intersection).
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The orbital period is one-half of a sidereal day, about 11 hours and 58 minutes, so that the satellites pass over the same locations or almost the same locations every day.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The orbits are arranged so that at least six satellites are always within line of sight from everywhere on the Earth's surface (see animation at right).
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The result of this objective is that the four satellites are not evenly spaced (90°) apart within each orbit.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] In general terms, the angular difference between satellites in each orbit is 30°, 105°, 120°, and 105° apart, which sum to 360°.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Orbiting at an altitude of approximately 20,200 km (12,600 mi); orbital radius of approximately 26,600 km (16,500 mi), each SV makes two complete orbits each sidereal day, repeating the same ground track each day.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] This was very helpful during development because even with only four satellites, correct alignment means all four are visible from one spot for a few hours each day.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] For military operations, the ground track repeat can be used to ensure good coverage in combat zones.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] As of February 2019, there are 31 satellites in the GPS constellation, 27 of which are in use at a given time with the rest allocated as stand-bys.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] A 32nd was launched in 2018, but as of July 2019 is still in evaluation.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] More decommissioned satellites are in orbit and available as spares.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The additional satellites improve the precision of GPS receiver calculations by providing redundant measurements.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] With the increased number of satellites, the constellation was changed to a nonuniform arrangement.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Such an arrangement was shown to improve accuracy but also improves reliability and availability of the system, relative to a uniform system, when multiple satellites fail.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] With the expanded constellation, nine satellites are usually visible at any time from any point on the Earth with a clear horizon, ensuring considerable redundancy over the minimum four satellites needed for a position.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The MCS can also access Satellite Control Network (SCN) ground antennas (for additional command and control capability) and NGA (National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency) monitor stations.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The flight paths of the satellites are tracked by dedicated U.S.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Space Force monitoring stations in Hawaii, Kwajalein Atoll, Ascension Island, Diego Garcia, Colorado Springs, Colorado and Cape Canaveral, Florida, along with shared NGA monitor stations operated in England, Argentina, Ecuador, Bahrain, Australia and Washington, DC.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The tracking information is sent to the MCS at Schriever Space Force Base 25 km (16 mi) ESE of Colorado Springs, which is operated by the 2nd Space Operations Squadron (2 SOPS) of the U.S.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Then 2 SOPS contacts each GPS satellite regularly with a navigational update using dedicated or shared (AFSCN) ground antennas (GPS dedicated ground antennas are located at Kwajalein, Ascension Island, Diego Garcia, and Cape Canaveral).
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] These updates synchronize the atomic clocks on board the satellites to within a few nanoseconds of each other, and adjust the ephemeris of each satellite's internal orbital model.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The updates are created by a Kalman filter that uses inputs from the ground monitoring stations, space weather information, and various other inputs.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] When a satellite's orbit is being adjusted, the satellite is marked *unhealthy*, so receivers do not use it.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] After the maneuver, engineers track the new orbit from the ground, upload the new ephemeris, and mark the satellite healthy again.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The operation control segment (OCS) currently serves as the control segment of record.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] It provides the operational capability that supports GPS users and keeps the GPS operational and performing within specification.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] OCS replaced the 1970s-era mainframe computer at Schriever Air Force Base in September 2007.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] After installation, the system helped enable upgrades and provide a foundation for a new security architecture that supported U.S. armed forces.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] OCS will continue to be the ground control system of record until the new segment, Next Generation GPS Operation Control System (OCX), is fully developed and functional.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Department of Defense has claimed that the new capabilities provided by OCX will be the cornerstone for enhancing GPS's mission capabilities, enabling U.S.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Space Force to enhance GPS operational services to U.S. combat forces, civil partners and domestic and international users.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The GPS OCX program also will reduce cost, schedule and technical risk.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] It is designed to provide 50% sustainment cost savings through efficient software architecture and Performance-Based Logistics.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] In addition, GPS OCX is expected to cost millions of dollars less than the cost to upgrade OCS while providing four times the capability.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The GPS OCX program represents a critical part of GPS modernization and provides information assurance improvements over the current GPS OCS program.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Air Force announced the completion of GPS OCX Preliminary Design Review and confirmed that the OCX program is ready for the next phase of development.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The GPS OCX program missed major milestones and pushed its launch into 2021, 5 years past the original deadline.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] According to the Government Accounting Office in 2019, the 2021 deadline looked shaky.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The project remained delayed in 2023, and was (as of June 2023) 73% over its original estimated budget.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] In late 2023, Frank Calvelli, the assistant secretary of the Air Force for space acquisitions and integration, stated that the project was estimated to go live some time during the summer of 2024.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The US Space Force accepted delivery of OCX Blocks I and II from contractor RTX on July 1, 2025, over 8 years behind schedule and roughly $4 billion over budget due to its monolithic development and constant feature creep while in process.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] If current Government Accountability Office estimates hold, the new system will enter service in December 2025.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] OCX Block 3F is currently in development to enable command and control of GPS IIIF satellites, currently slated to begin launching in 2027.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] The user segment (US) is composed of hundreds of thousands of U.S. and allied military users of the secure GPS Precise Positioning Service, and tens of millions of civil, commercial and scientific users of the Standard Positioning Service.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] In general, GPS receivers are composed of an antenna, tuned to the frequencies transmitted by the satellites, receiver-processors, and a highly stable clock (often a crystal oscillator).
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] They may also include a display for providing location and speed information to the user.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] GPS receivers may include an input for differential corrections, using the RTCM SC-104 format.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] This is typically in the form of an RS-232 port at 4,800 bit/s speed.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Data is actually sent at a much lower rate, which limits the accuracy of the signal sent using RTCM.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Receivers with internal DGPS receivers can outperform those using external RTCM data.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] As of 2006, even low-cost units commonly include Wide Area Augmentation System (WAAS) receivers.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Many GPS receivers can relay position data to a PC or other device using the NMEA 0183 protocol.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Although this protocol is officially defined by the National Marine Electronics Association (NMEA), references to this protocol have been compiled from public records, allowing open source tools like gpsd to read the protocol without violating intellectual property laws.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Other proprietary protocols exist as well, such as the SiRF and MTK protocols.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p01] Receivers can interface with other devices using methods including a serial connection, USB, or Bluetooth.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] While originally a military project, GPS is considered a dual-use technology, meaning it has significant civilian applications as well.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] GPS has become a widely deployed and useful tool for commerce, scientific uses, tracking, and surveillance.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] GPS's accurate time facilitates everyday activities such as banking, mobile phone operations, and even the control of power grids by allowing well synchronized hand-off switching.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Many civilian applications use one or more of GPS's three basic components: absolute location, relative movement, and time transfer.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The U.S. government controls the export of some civilian receivers.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] This rule applies even to otherwise purely civilian units that only receive the L1 frequency and the C/A (Coarse/Acquisition) code.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Disabling operation above these limits exempts the receiver from classification as a munition.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The rule refers to operation at both the target altitude and speed, but some receivers stop operating even when stationary.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] This has caused problems with some amateur radio balloon launches that regularly reach 30 km (100,000 ft).
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] These limits only apply to units or components exported from the United States.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] A growing trade in various components exists, including GPS units from other countries.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] GPS type navigation was first used in war in the 1991 Persian Gulf War, before GPS was fully developed in 1995, to assist Coalition Forces to navigate and perform maneuvers in the war.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The war also demonstrated the vulnerability of GPS to being jammed, when Iraqi forces installed jamming devices on likely targets that emitted radio noise, disrupting reception of the weak GPS signal.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] GPS's vulnerability to jamming is a threat that continues to grow as jamming equipment and experience grows.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] GPS signals have been reported to have been jammed many times over the years for military purposes.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Russia seems to have several objectives for this approach, such as intimidating neighbors while undermining confidence in their reliance on American systems, promoting their GLONASS alternative, disrupting Western military exercises, and protecting assets from drones.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] China uses jamming to discourage US surveillance aircraft near the contested Spratly Islands.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] North Korea has mounted several major jamming operations near its border with South Korea and offshore, disrupting flights, shipping and fishing operations.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Iranian Armed Forces disrupted the civilian airliner plane Flight PS752's GPS when it shot down the aircraft.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] In the Russo-Ukrainian War, GPS-guided munitions provided to Ukraine by NATO countries experienced significant failure rates as a result of Russian electronic warfare.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Excalibur artillery shells efficiency rate hitting targets dropped from 70% to 6% as Russia adapted its electronic warfare activities.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] While most clocks derive their time from Coordinated Universal Time (UTC), the atomic clocks on the satellites are set to *GPS time*.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The difference is that GPS time is not corrected to match the rotation of the Earth, so it does not contain new leap seconds or other corrections that are periodically added to UTC.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] GPS time was set to match UTC in 1980, but has since diverged.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The lack of corrections means that GPS time remains at a constant offset with International Atomic Time (TAI) (TAI – GPS = 19 seconds).
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Periodic corrections are performed to the on-board clocks to keep them synchronized with ground clocks.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The GPS navigation message includes the difference between GPS time and UTC.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] As of January 2017, GPS time is 18 seconds ahead of UTC because of the leap second added to UTC on December 31, 2016.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Receivers subtract this offset from GPS time to calculate UTC and specific time zone values.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] New GPS units may not show the correct UTC time until after receiving the UTC offset message.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The GPS-UTC offset field can accommodate 255 leap seconds (eight bits).
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] GPS time is theoretically accurate to about 14 nanoseconds, due to the clock drift relative to International Atomic Time that the atomic clocks in GPS transmitters experience.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Most receivers lose some accuracy in their interpretation of the signals and are only accurate to about 100 nanoseconds.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The GPS implements two major corrections to its time signals for relativistic effects: one for relative velocity of satellite and receiver, using the special theory of relativity, and one for the difference in gravitational potential between satellite and receiver, using general relativity.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The acceleration of the satellite could also be computed independently as a correction, depending on purpose, but normally the effect is already dealt with in the first two corrections.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] As opposed to the year, month, and day format of the Gregorian calendar, the GPS date is expressed as a week number and a seconds-into-week number.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The week number is transmitted as a ten-bit field in the C/A and P(Y) navigation messages, and so it becomes zero again every 1,024 weeks (19.6 years).
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] It happened the second time at 23:59:42 UTC on April 6, 2019.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] To determine the current Gregorian date, a GPS receiver must be provided with the approximate date (to within 3,584 days) to correctly translate the GPS date signal.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] To address this concern in the future the modernized GPS civil navigation (CNAV) message uses a 13-bit field that only repeats every 8,192 weeks (157 years), thus lasting until 2137 (157 years after GPS week zero).
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The navigational signals transmitted by GPS satellites encode a variety of information including satellite positions, the state of the internal clocks, and the health of the network.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] These signals are transmitted on two separate carrier frequencies that are common to all satellites in the network.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Two different encodings are used: a public encoding that enables lower resolution navigation, and an encrypted encoding used by the U.S. military.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Each GPS satellite continuously broadcasts a *navigation message* on L1 (C/A and P/Y) and L2 (P/Y) frequencies at a rate of 50 bits per second (see bitrate).
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Each complete message takes 750 seconds (12+1⁄2 minutes) to complete.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The message structure has a basic format of a 1500-bit-long frame made up of five subframes, each subframe being 300 bits (6 seconds) long.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Subframes 4 and 5 are subcommutated 25 times each, so that a complete data message requires the transmission of 25 full frames.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Each subframe consists of ten words, each 30 bits long.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Thus, with 300 bits in a subframe times 5 subframes in a frame times 25 frames in a message, each message is 37,500 bits long.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] At a transmission rate of 50-bit/s, this gives 750 seconds to transmit an entire almanac message (GPS).
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Each 30-second frame begins precisely on the minute or half-minute as indicated by the atomic clock on each satellite.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The first subframe of each frame encodes the week number and the time within the week, as well as the data about the health of the satellite.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The second and the third subframes contain the *ephemeris* – the precise orbital parameters for the satellite.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The fourth and fifth subframes contain the *almanac*, which contains coarse orbit and status information for up to 32 satellites in the constellation as well as data related to error correction.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Thus, to obtain an accurate satellite location from this transmitted message, the receiver must demodulate the message from each satellite it includes in its solution for 18 to 30 seconds.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] To collect all transmitted almanacs, the receiver must demodulate the message for 732 to 750 seconds or 12+1⁄2 minutes.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] All satellites broadcast at the same frequencies, encoding signals using unique code-division multiple access (CDMA) so receivers can distinguish individual satellites from each other.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The system uses two distinct CDMA encoding types: the coarse/acquisition (C/A) code, which is accessible by the general public, and the precise (P(Y)) code, which is encrypted so that only the U.S. military and other NATO nations who have been given access to the encryption code can access it.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The ephemeris is updated every 2 hours and is sufficiently stable for 4 hours, with provisions for updates every 6 hours or longer in non-nominal conditions.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The almanac is updated typically every 24 hours.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Additionally, data for a few weeks following is uploaded in case of transmission updates that delay data upload.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] All satellites broadcast at the same two frequencies, 1.57542 GHz (L1 signal) and 1.2276 GHz (L2 signal).
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The satellite network uses a CDMA spread-spectrum technique where the low-bitrate message data is encoded with a high-rate pseudo-random (PRN) sequence that is different for each satellite.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The receiver must be aware of the PRN codes for each satellite to reconstruct the actual message data.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The C/A code, for civilian use, transmits data at 1.023 million chips per second, whereas the P code, for U.S. military use, transmits at 10.23 million chips per second.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The actual internal reference of the satellites is 10.22999999543 MHz to compensate for relativistic effects that make observers on the Earth perceive a different time reference with respect to the transmitters in orbit.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The L1 carrier is modulated by both the C/A and P codes, while the L2 carrier is only modulated by the P code.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The P code can be encrypted as a so-called P(Y) code that is only available to military equipment with a proper decryption key.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Both the C/A and P(Y) codes impart the precise time-of-day to the user.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The L3 signal at a frequency of 1.38105 GHz is used to transmit data from the satellites to ground stations.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] This data is used by the United States Nuclear Detonation (NUDET) Detection System (USNDS) to detect, locate, and report nuclear detonations (NUDETs) in the Earth's atmosphere and near space.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] One usage is the enforcement of nuclear test ban treaties.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The L4 band at 1.379913 GHz is being studied for additional ionospheric correction.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The L5 frequency band at 1.17645 GHz was added in the process of GPS modernization.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] This frequency falls into an internationally protected range for aeronautical navigation, promising little or no interference under all circumstances.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The first Block IIF satellite that provides this signal was launched in May 2010.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] On February 5, 2016, the 12th and final Block IIF satellite was launched.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The L5 consists of two carrier components that are in phase quadrature with each other.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Each carrier component is bi-phase shift key (BPSK) modulated by a separate bit train.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] In 2011, a conditional waiver was granted to LightSquared to operate a terrestrial broadband service near the L1 band.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The GPS community had not objected to the LightSquared (formerly MSV and SkyTerra) applications until November 2010, when LightSquared applied for a modification to its Ancillary Terrestrial Component (ATC) authorization.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] This filing (SAT-MOD-20101118-00239) amounted to a request to run several orders of magnitude more power in the same frequency band for terrestrial base stations, essentially repurposing what was supposed to be a "quiet neighborhood" for signals from space as the equivalent of a cellular network.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Testing in the first half of 2011 has demonstrated that the effects from the lower 10 MHz of spectrum are minimal to GPS devices (less than 1% of the total GPS devices are affected).
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The upper 10 MHz intended for use by LightSquared may have some effect on GPS devices.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] There is some concern that this may seriously degrade the GPS signal for many consumer uses.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] *Aviation Week* magazine reports that the latest testing (June 2011) confirms "significant jamming" of GPS by LightSquared's system.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Because all of the satellite signals are modulated onto the same L1 carrier frequency, the signals must be separated after demodulation.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] This is done by assigning each satellite a unique binary sequence known as a Gold code.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The signals are decoded after demodulation using addition of the Gold codes corresponding to the satellites monitored by the receiver.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] If the almanac information has previously been acquired, the receiver picks the satellites to listen for by their PRNs, unique numbers in the range 1 through 32.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] If the almanac information is not in memory, the receiver enters a search mode until a lock is obtained on one of the satellites.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] To obtain a lock, it is necessary that there be an unobstructed line of sight from the receiver to the satellite.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The receiver can then acquire the almanac and determine the satellites it should listen for.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] As it detects each satellite's signal, it identifies it by its distinct C/A code pattern.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] There can be a delay of up to 30 seconds before the first estimate of position because of the need to read the ephemeris data.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Processing of the navigation message enables the determination of the time of transmission and the satellite position at this time.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] For more information see Demodulation and Decoding, Advanced.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The receiver uses messages received from satellites to determine the satellite positions and time sent.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The *x, y,* and *z* components of satellite position and the time sent (*s*) are designated as [*xi, yi, zi, si*] where the subscript *i* denotes the satellite and has the value 1, 2, ..., *n*, where *n* ≥ 4.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] When the time of message reception indicated by the on-board receiver clock is ${\tilde {t}}_{i}$ , the true reception time is $t_{i}={\tilde {t}}_{i}-b$ , where *b* is the receiver's clock bias from the much more accurate GPS clocks employed by the satellites.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The receiver clock bias is the same for all received satellite signals (assuming the satellite clocks are all perfectly synchronized).
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The message's transit time is ${\tilde {t}}_{i}-b-s_{i}$ , where *si* is the satellite time.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Assuming the message traveled at the speed of light, *c*, the distance traveled is $\left({\tilde {t}}_{i}-b-s_{i}\right)c$ .
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Since the equations have four unknowns [*x, y, z, b*]—the three components of GPS receiver position and the clock bias—signals from at least four satellites are necessary to attempt solving these equations.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] They can be solved by algebraic or numerical methods.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Existence and uniqueness of GPS solutions are discussed by Abell and Chaffee.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] When *n* is greater than four, this system is overdetermined and a fitting method must be used.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The amount of error in the results varies with the received satellites' locations in the sky, since certain configurations (when the received satellites are close together in the sky) cause larger errors.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Receivers usually calculate a running estimate of the error in the calculated position.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] This is done by multiplying the basic resolution of the receiver by quantities called the geometric dilution of position (GDOP) factors, calculated from the relative sky directions of the satellites used.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The receiver location is expressed in a specific coordinate system, such as latitude and longitude using the WGS 84 geodetic datum or a country-specific system.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The GPS equations can be solved by numerical and analytical methods.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Geometrical interpretations can enhance the understanding of these solution methods.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The measured ranges, called pseudoranges, contain clock errors.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] In a simplified idealization in which the ranges are synchronized, these true ranges represent the radii of spheres, each centered on one of the transmitting satellites.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The solution for the position of the receiver is then at the intersection of the surfaces of these spheres; see trilateration (more generally, true-range multilateration).
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Signals from at minimum three satellites are required, and their three spheres would typically intersect at two points.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] One of the points is the location of the receiver, and the other moves rapidly in successive measurements and would not usually be on Earth's surface.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] In practice, there are many sources of inaccuracy besides clock bias, including random errors as well as the potential for precision loss from subtracting numbers close to each other if the centers of the spheres are relatively close together.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] This means that the position calculated from three satellites alone is unlikely to be accurate enough.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Data from more satellites can help because of the tendency for random errors to cancel out and also by giving a larger spread between the sphere centers.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] But at the same time, more spheres will not generally intersect at one point.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Therefore, a near intersection gets computed, typically via least squares.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The more signals available, the better the approximation is likely to be.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] If the pseudorange between the receiver and satellite *i* and the pseudorange between the receiver and satellite *j* are subtracted, *pi* − *pj*, the common receiver clock bias (*b*) cancels out, resulting in a difference of distances *di* − *dj*.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The locus of points having a constant difference in distance to two points (here, two satellites) is a hyperbola on a plane and a hyperboloid of revolution (more specifically, a two-sheeted hyperboloid) in 3D space (see Multilateration).
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Thus, from four pseudorange measurements, the receiver can be placed at the intersection of the surfaces of three hyperboloids each with foci at a pair of satellites.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] With additional satellites, the multiple intersections are not necessarily unique, and a best-fitting solution is sought instead.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The receiver position can be interpreted as the center of an inscribed sphere (insphere) of radius *bc*, given by the receiver clock bias *b* (scaled by the speed of light *c*).
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The insphere location is such that it touches other spheres.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The circumscribing spheres are centered at the GPS satellites, whose radii equal the measured pseudoranges *p*i.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] This configuration is distinct from the one described above, in which the spheres' radii were the unbiased or geometric ranges *d*i.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The clock in the receiver is usually not of the same quality as the ones in the satellites and will not be accurately synchronized to them.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] This produces pseudoranges with large differences compared to the true distances to the satellites.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Therefore, in practice, the time difference between the receiver clock and the satellite time is defined as an unknown clock bias *b*.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The equations are then solved simultaneously for the receiver position and the clock bias.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The solution space [*x, y, z, b*] can be seen as a four-dimensional spacetime, and signals from at minimum four satellites are needed.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] In that case each of the equations describes a hypercone (or spherical cone), with the cusp located at the satellite, and the base a sphere around the satellite.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The receiver is at the intersection of four or more of such hypercones.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] When more than four satellites are available, the calculation can use the four best, or more than four simultaneously (up to all visible satellites), depending on the number of receiver channels, processing capability, and geometric dilution of precision (GDOP).
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Using more than four involves an over-determined system of equations with no unique solution; such a system can be solved by a least-squares or weighted least squares method.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Both the equations for four satellites, or the least squares equations for more than four, are non-linear and need special solution methods.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] A common approach is by iteration on a linearized form of the equations, such as the Gauss–Newton algorithm.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The GPS was initially developed assuming use of a numerical least-squares solution method—i.e., before closed-form solutions were found.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] One closed-form solution to the above set of equations was developed by S.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Its properties are well known; in particular, proponents claim it is superior in low-GDOP situations, compared to iterative least squares methods.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Bancroft's method is algebraic, as opposed to numerical, and can be used for four or more satellites.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] When four satellites are used, the key steps are inversion of a 4x4 matrix and solution of a single-variable quadratic equation.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Bancroft's method provides one or two solutions for the unknown quantities.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] When there are two (usually the case), only one is a near-Earth sensible solution.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] When a receiver uses more than four satellites for a solution, Bancroft uses the generalized inverse (i.e., the pseudoinverse) to find a solution.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] A case has been made that iterative methods, such as the Gauss–Newton algorithm approach for solving over-determined non-linear least squares problems, generally provide more accurate solutions.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] (2015) states that "Bancroft's (1985) solution is a very early, if not the first, closed-form solution." Other closed-form solutions were published afterwards, although their adoption in practice is unclear.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] GPS error analysis examines error sources in GPS results and the expected size of those errors.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] GPS makes corrections for receiver clock errors and other effects, but some residual errors remain uncorrected.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Error sources include signal arrival time measurements, numerical calculations, atmospheric effects (ionospheric/tropospheric delays), ephemeris and clock data, multipath signals, and natural and artificial interference.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Magnitude of residual errors from these sources depends on geometric dilution of precision.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Artificial errors may result from jamming devices and threaten ships and aircraft or from intentional signal degradation through selective availability, which limited accuracy to ≈ 6–12 m (20–40 ft), but has been switched off since May 1, 2000.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] GNSS enhancement refers to techniques used to improve the accuracy of positioning information provided by the Global Positioning System or other global navigation satellite systems in general, a network of satellites used for navigation.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Enhancement methods of improving accuracy rely on external information being integrated into the calculation process.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] There are many such systems in place and they are generally named or described based on how the GPS sensor receives the information.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] In the United States, GPS receivers are regulated under the Federal Communications Commission's (FCC) Part 15 rules.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] As indicated in the manuals of GPS-enabled devices sold in the United States, as a Part 15 device, it "must accept any interference received, including interference that may cause undesired operation".
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] With respect to GPS devices in particular, the FCC states that GPS receiver manufacturers "must use receivers that reasonably discriminate against reception of signals outside their allocated spectrum".
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] For the last 30 years, GPS receivers have operated next to the Mobile Satellite Service band, and have discriminated against reception of mobile satellite services, such as Inmarsat, without any issue.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The spectrum allocated for GPS L1 use by the FCC is 1559 to 1610 MHz, while the spectrum allocated for satellite-to-ground use owned by LightSquared is the Mobile Satellite Service band.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Since 1996, the FCC has authorized licensed use of the spectrum neighboring the GPS band of 1525 to 1559 MHz to the Virginia company LightSquared.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] On March 1, 2001, the FCC received an application from LightSquared's predecessor, Motient Services, to use their allocated frequencies for an integrated satellite-terrestrial service.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] GPS Industry Council came to an out-of-band-emissions (OOBE) agreement with LightSquared to prevent transmissions from LightSquared's ground-based stations from emitting transmissions into the neighboring GPS band of 1559 to 1610 MHz.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] We do not intend, nor will we permit, the terrestrial component to become a stand-alone service." This authorization was reviewed and approved by the U.S.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Interdepartment Radio Advisory Committee, which includes the U.S.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Coast Guard, Federal Aviation Administration, National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA), U.S.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The January 2011 order makes final authorization contingent upon studies of GPS interference issues carried out by a LightSquared led working group along with GPS industry and Federal agency participation.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] On February 14, 2012, the FCC initiated proceedings to vacate LightSquared's Conditional Waiver Order based on the NTIA's conclusion that there was currently no practical way to mitigate potential GPS interference.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] GPS receiver manufacturers design GPS receivers to use spectrum beyond the GPS-allocated band.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] In some cases, GPS receivers are designed to use up to 400 MHz of spectrum in either direction of the L1 frequency of 1575.42 MHz, because mobile satellite services in those regions are broadcasting from space to ground, and at power levels commensurate with mobile satellite services.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] As regulated under the FCC's Part 15 rules, GPS receivers are not warranted protection from signals outside GPS-allocated spectrum.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] This is why GPS operates next to the Mobile Satellite Service band, and also why the Mobile Satellite Service band operates next to GPS.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The symbiotic relationship of spectrum allocation ensures that users of both bands are able to operate cooperatively and freely.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The FCC adopted rules in February 2003 that allowed Mobile Satellite Service (MSS) licensees such as LightSquared to construct a small number of ancillary ground-based towers in their licensed spectrum to "promote more efficient use of terrestrial wireless spectrum".
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] MSS ATC is unlikely to compete directly with terrestrial CMRS for the same customer base...".
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] In 2004, the FCC clarified that the ground-based towers would be ancillary, noting: "We will authorize MSS ATC subject to conditions that ensure that the added terrestrial component remains ancillary to the principal MSS offering.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] To build public support of efforts to continue the 2004 FCC authorization of LightSquared's ancillary terrestrial component vs. a simple ground-based LTE service in the Mobile Satellite Service band, GPS receiver manufacturer Trimble Navigation Ltd. formed the "Coalition To Save Our GPS".
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The FCC and LightSquared have each made public commitments to solve the GPS interference issue before the network is allowed to operate.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] According to Chris Dancy of the Aircraft Owners and Pilots Association, airline pilots with the type of systems that would be affected "may go off course and not even realize it".
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The problems could also affect the Federal Aviation Administration upgrade to the air traffic control system, United States Defense Department guidance, and local emergency services including 911.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] LightSquared is challenging the FCC's action.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] Following the United States's deployment of GPS, other countries have also developed their own satellite navigation systems.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] In the event of adverse space weather or the deployment of an anti-satellite weapon against GPS, the United States has no terrestrial backup system.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The potential cost of such an event to the U.S. economy is estimated at $1 billion per day.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] The LORAN-C system was turned off in North America in 2010 and Europe in 2015. eLoran is proposed as an American terrestrial backup system, but as of 2024 has not received approval or funding.
[src:precision-agriculture/global-positioning-system-p02] China continues to operate LORAN-C transmitters, and Russia has a similar system called CHAYKA ("Seagull").
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] A central component of implementing this strategy is the satellite monitoring of agricultural machinery, which forms the basis for modern farm fleet management.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] This is achieved through the use of fleet telematics systems, where vehicles are equipped with a GPS tracking unit and an onboard controller that transmits telemetry data—such as location, speed, engine hours, and fuel consumption—to a central server for analysis.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] This stream of real-time data allows for the automation of agricultural operations and provides critical insights for improving diagnosis and decision-making.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] The practice of precision agriculture has been enabled by the advent of GPS and GNSS.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Similar data is collected by sensor arrays mounted on GPS-equipped combine harvesters.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] These arrays consist of real-time sensors that measure everything from chlorophyll levels to plant water status, along with multispectral imagery.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] This data is used in conjunction with satellite imagery by variable rate technology (VRT) including seeders, sprayers, etc. to optimally distribute resources.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] However, recent technological advances have enabled the use of real-time sensors directly in soil, which can wirelessly transmit data without the need of human presence.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Precision agriculture can benefit from unmanned aerial vehicles, that are relatively inexpensive and can be operated by novice pilots.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] These agricultural drones can be equipped with multispectral or RGB cameras to capture many images of a field that can be stitched together using photogrammetric methods to create orthophotos.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] These multispectral images contain multiple values per pixel in addition to the traditional red, green blue values such as near infrared and red-edge spectrum values used to process and analyze vegetative indexes such as NDVI maps.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] These drones are capable of capturing imagery and providing additional geographical references such as elevation, which allows software to perform map algebra functions to build precise topography maps.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] These topographic maps can be used to correlate crop health with topography, the results of which can be used to optimize crop inputs such as water, fertilizer or chemicals such as herbicides and growth regulators through variable rate applications.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Precision agriculture is a key component of the third wave of modern agricultural revolutions.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] The first agricultural revolution was the increase of mechanized agriculture, from 1900 to 1930.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Each farmer produced enough food to feed about 26 people during this time.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] The 1960s prompted the Green Revolution with new methods of genetic modification, which led to each farmer feeding about 156 people.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] It is expected that by 2050, the global population will reach about 9.6 billion, and food production must effectively double from current levels in order to feed every mouth.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] With new technological advancements in the agricultural revolution of precision farming, each farmer will be able to feed 265 people on the same acreage.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] The first wave of the precision agricultural revolution came in the forms of satellite and aerial imagery, weather prediction, variable rate fertilizer application, and crop health indicators.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] The second wave aggregates the machine data for even more precise planting, topographical mapping, and soil data.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Precision agriculture uses many tools, but some of the basics include tractors, combines, sprayers, planters, and diggers, which are all considered auto-guidance systems.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] The small devices on the equipment that use GIS (geographic information system) are what makes precision agriculture what it is; the GIS system can be thought of as the “brain”.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] To be able to use precision agriculture, the equipment needs to be wired with the right technology and data systems.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] More tools include Variable rate technology (VRT), Global positioning system, Geographical information system, Grid sampling, and remote sensors.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Geolocating a field enables the farmer to overlay information gathered from the analysis of soils and residual nitrogen, and information on previous crops and soil resistivity.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Intra and inter-field variability may result from a number of factors.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] These include climatic conditions (hail, drought, rain, etc.), soils (texture, depth, nitrogen levels), cropping practices (no-till farming), weeds, and disease.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Permanent indicators—chiefly soil indicators—provide farmers with information about the main environmental constants.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Point indicators allow them to track a crop's status, i.e., to see whether diseases are developing, if the crop is suffering from water stress, nitrogen stress, or lodging, whether it has been damaged by ice, and so on.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] This information may come from weather stations and other sensors (soil electrical resistivity, detection with the naked eye, satellite imagery, etc.).
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Soil resistivity measurements combined with soil analysis make it possible to measure moisture content.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Soil resistivity is also a relatively simple and cheap measurement.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] It is important to realize why PA technology is or is not adopted, "for PA technology adoption to occur the farmer has to perceive the technology as useful and easy to use.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] New information and communication technologies make field-level crop management more operational and easier to achieve for farmers.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Application of crop management decisions calls for agricultural equipment that supports variable-rate technology (VRT), for example varying seed density along with the variable-rate application (VRA) of nitrogen and phytosanitary products.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] The concept of precision agriculture first emerged in the United States in the early 1980s.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] In 1985, researchers at the University of Minnesota varied lime inputs in crop fields.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] It was also at this time that the practice of grid sampling appeared (applying a fixed grid of one sample per hectare).
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Towards the end of the 1980s, this technique was used to derive the first input recommendation maps for fertilizers and pH corrections.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] The use of yield sensors developed from new technologies, combined with the advent of GPS receivers, has been gaining ground ever since.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Today, such systems cover several million hectares.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] In the American Midwest (US), it is associated not with sustainable agriculture but with mainstream farmers who are trying to maximize profits by spending money only in areas that require fertilizer.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] This practice allows the farmer to vary the rate of fertilizer across the field according to the need identified by GPS guided Grid or Zone Sampling.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Fertilizer that would have been spread in areas that do not need it can be placed in areas in need, thereby optimizing its use.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Around the world, precision agriculture developed at a varying pace.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Precursor nations were the United States, Canada and Australia.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] In Europe, the United Kingdom was the first to go down this path, followed closely by France, where it first appeared in 1997–1998.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] In Latin America the leading country is Argentina, where it was introduced in the middle 1990s with the support of the National Agricultural Technology Institute.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Brazil established a state-owned enterprise, Embrapa, to research and develop sustainable agriculture.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] The development of GPS and variable-rate spreading techniques helped to anchor precision farming management practices.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Today, less than 10% of France's farmers are equipped with variable-rate systems.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Uptake of GPS is more widespread, but this hasn't stopped them using precision agriculture services, which supplies field-level recommendation maps.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] While digital technologies can transform the landscape of agricultural machinery, making mechanization both more precise and more accessible, non-mechanized production is still dominant in many low- and middle-income countries, especially in sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Research on precision agriculture for non-mechanized production is increasing and so is its adoption.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Examples include the AgroCares hand-held soil scanner, uncrewed aerial vehicle (UAV) services (also known as drones), and GNSS to map field boundaries and establish land tenure.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] However, it is not clear how many agricultural producers actually use digital technologies.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Precision livestock farming supports farmers in real-time by continuously monitoring and controlling animal productivity, environmental impacts, and health and welfare parameters.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Sensors attached to animals or to barn equipment operate climate control and monitor animals’ health status, movement and needs.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] For example, cows can be tagged with the electronic identification (EID) that allows a milking robot to access a database of udder coordinates for specific cows.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Global automatic milking system sales have increased over recent years, but adoption is likely mostly in Northern Europe, and likely almost absent in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Automated feeding machines for both cows and poultry also exist, but data and evidence regarding their adoption trends and drivers is likewise scarce.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Therefore, China is trying to better introduce precision agriculture technology into its own country and reduce some risks, paving the way for China's technology to develop precision agriculture in the future.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] In December 2014, the Russian President made an address to the Russian Parliament where he called for a National Technology Initiative.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] It is divided into subcomponents such as the FoodNet initiative.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] The FoodNet initiative contains a set of declared priorities, such as precision agriculture.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] This field is of special interest to Russia as an important tool in developing elements of the bioeconomy in Russia.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Precision agriculture, as the name implies, means the application of precise and correct amounts of inputs like water, fertilizer, pesticides, etc. at the correct time to the crop to increase its productivity and maximize its yields.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Precision agriculture management practices can significantly reduce the amount of nutrient and other crop inputs used while boosting yields.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Farmers thus obtain a return on their investment by saving on water, pesticide, and fertilizer costs.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] The second, larger-scale benefit of targeting inputs concerns environmental impacts.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Applying the right amount of chemicals in the right place and at the right time benefits crops, soils and groundwater, and thus the entire crop cycle.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Consequently, precision agriculture has become a cornerstone of sustainable agriculture, since it respects crops, soils and farmers.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Sustainable agriculture seeks to assure a continued supply of food within the ecological, economic and social limits required to sustain production in the long term.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] A 2013 article tried to show that precision agriculture can help farmers in developing countries like India.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Precision agriculture reduces the pressure of agriculture on the environment by increasing the efficiency of machinery and putting it into use.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] For example, the use of fleet digitalization techniques and GPS trackers reduces fuel consumption for agriculture, while variable rate application of nutrients or pesticides can potentially reduce the use of these inputs, thereby saving costs and reducing harmful runoff into the waterways.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] GPS also reduces the amount of compaction to the ground by following previously made guidance lines.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] This will also allow for less time in the field and reduce the environmental impact of the equipment and chemicals.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Precision agriculture produces large quantities of varied sensing data which creates an opportunity to adapt and reuse such data for archaeology and heritage work, enhancing understanding of archaeology in contemporary agricultural landscapes.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Precision agriculture is an application of breakthrough digital farming technologies.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Over $4.6 billion has been invested in agriculture tech companies—sometimes called agtech.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Driverless tractors have advanced significantly in the 2000s.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] The tractor does most of the work, with the farmer stepping in for emergencies.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Technology is advancing towards driverless machinery programmed by GPS to spread fertilizer or plow land.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Autonomy of technology is driven by the demanding need for diagnoses, often difficult to accomplish solely by hands-on farmer-operated machinery.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] In many instances of high rates of production, manual adjustments cannot be sustained.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Other innovations include, partly solar powered, machines/robots that identify weeds and precisely kill them with a dose of a herbicide or lasers.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Agricultural robots have been used for applications including weed control, herbicide application, picking, harvesting, seeding, and planting.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Advanced harvesting robots are being developed to identify ripe fruits, adjust to their shape and size, and carefully pluck them from branches.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Drone and satellite technology are used in precision farming.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] This often occurs when drones take high-quality images while satellites capture the bigger picture.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Aerial photography from light aircraft can be combined with data from satellite records to predict future yields based on the current level of field biomass.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Aggregated images can create contour maps to track where water flows, determine variable-rate seeding, and create yield maps of areas that were more or less productive.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] The Internet of things is the network of physical objects outfitted with electronics that enable data collection and aggregation.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] IoT comes into play with the development of sensors and farm-management software.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] For example, farmers can spectroscopically measure nitrogen, phosphorus, and potassium in liquid manure, which is notoriously inconsistent.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] They can then scan the ground to see where cows have already urinated and apply fertilizer to only the spots that need it.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Moisture sensors in the soil determine the best times to remotely water plants.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] The irrigation systems can be programmed to switch which side of the tree trunk they water based on the plant's need and rainfall.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Innovations are not just limited to plants—they can be used for the welfare of animals.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Cattle can be outfitted with internal sensors to keep track of stomach acidity and digestive problems.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] External sensors track movement patterns to determine the cow's health and fitness, sense physical injuries, and identify the optimal times for breeding.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] All this data from sensors can be aggregated and analyzed to detect trends and patterns.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] As another example, monitoring technology can be used to make beekeeping more efficient.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Honeybees are of significant economic value and provide a vital service to agriculture by pollinating a variety of crops.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Monitoring of a honeybee colony's health via wireless temperature, humidity, and CO2 sensors helps to improve the productivity of bees, and to read early warnings in the data that might threaten the very survival of an entire hive.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Smartphone and tablet applications are becoming increasingly popular in precision agriculture.
[src:precision-agriculture/precision-agriculture] Smartphones come with many useful applications already installed, including the camera, microphone, GPS, and accelerometer.
